<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, June 23, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Makes Probe Transcript Public
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In sometimes sharp exchanges, Vice President Al Gore told
investigators that he does not know ''to this day'' that a controversial 1996
Buddhist temple event was a Democratic fund-raising event, a transcript released
Friday by the White House shows. Moving aggressively to respond to re-emergence
of the fund-raising controversy in his presidential campaign, Gore said he made
the transcript public so Americans can judge for themselves: ''I've told the
truth.'' Gore acted after word leaked that Robert Conrad, the Justice Department
prosecutor who questioned the vice president on April 18, is recommending that a
special counsel be appointed to probe the truthfulness of the vice president's
answers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Australia Hostel Fire Cause
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHILDERS, Australia (AP) -- Backpacker Darrin Hill had just dropped off to
sleep after a 12-hour day picking tomatoes when he was startled by the sound of
breaking glass and the smell of smoke. The blaze at the 100-year-old Palace
Backpackers' Hostel tore quickly through the wooden structure, sending guests
leaping from the second floor onto the roof of a neighboring clothing store.
Survivors complained that some of the windows were barred. Fire officials said
the building had regular safety checks and was equipped with smoke detectors,
but some of the survivors told police they had not heard any alarms.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Hostage Release Talks Resume
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Talks between Fiji's military rulers and gunmen holding 31
members of the deposed government hostage broke down for several hours Saturday,
dampening hopes the captives would be released soon. But negotiations resumed in
the afternoon. Military commander Commodore Frank Bainimarama and rebel leader
George Speight met Saturday to look over the final draft of an accord which
negotiators on both sides said Friday would pave the way for the hostages'
release. But Bainimarama left the meeting after less than 20 minutes without
signing the accord, a military spokesman told The Associated Press on condition
of anonymity. Bainimarama returned to the meeting a few hours later, however,
signaling a resumption of talks.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Officials Identify 4th Barrel Body
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HARRISONVILLE, Mo. (AP) -- Authorities have identified the fourth of five
female bodies found stuffed in barrels in Kansas and Missouri. The body of
Sheila Dale Faith, 51, of Fullerton, Calif., was one of three found June 5 in a
Raymore storage locker rented by John Edward Robinson Sr., prosecutor Chris
Koster said Friday. The identification was made by new dental records, he said.
Robinson, 56, of Olathe, Kan., has been charged with three counts of
first-degree murder, and is being held on $5 million bond. Two other bodies were
found June 3 on a tract owned by Robinson near La Cygne, Kan., about 40 miles
west of Raymore.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Taped Reno Deposition at Waco Trial
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WACO, Texas (AP) -- Federal agents had the discretion to do what needed to be
done during the final day of the Branch Davidian standoff, to insert tear gas to
flush sect members out of the compound, Attorney General Janet Reno said in a
videotaped deposition played for jurors Friday. The plan, approved by Reno
called for FBI agents to use tank booms to gradually insert tear gas in the
building. If after 48 hours the tear-gassing plan was ineffective, then agents
could begin the systematic dismantling of the compound.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuba: Elian Case Looks Favorable
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Cuba called today's decision by a U.S. federal appeals court
not to review the Elian Gonzalez case ''favorable,'' but warned that the
6-year-old refugee's Miami relatives would likely continue to try to block his
return home. Following the unanimous decision of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Atlanta, brief official bulletins were issued on state-run television
and radio. In Miami, the relatives said they will file an appeal with the U.S.
Supreme Court on Monday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 29; Nasdaq Falls 92
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, with blue-chip shares rising and
technology stocks coming under selling pressure again as investors locked in
profits following a weeks-long runup. The Dow Jones industrials ended up 28.63
at 10,404.75, according to preliminary calculations. On the NYSE, losers led
gainers by a 7-to-5 margin. The technology-laden Nasdaq fell 91.50 points to
3,845.34.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
White Sox Beat Yankees 4-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Carlos Lee hit a game-tying homer against Mariano Rivera
leading off the ninth and Jose Valentin singled home the winning run later in
the inning as the Chicago White Sox stunned the New York Yankees 4-3 Friday
night. Chicago, which outscored New York 42-17 in sweeping a four-game series
last week at Yankee Stadium, has won 17 of 21 overall. After the Yankees left
the bases loaded against Sean Lowe (2-1) in the top half, Lee hit Rivera's first
pitch of the bottom half for his 14th homer.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER
</SUBHEAD>
