<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Backs Money For Tobacco Suit  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tobacco industry officials and their
congressional allies are upset with the bipartisan House vote to
provide the Justice Department with enough money to keep alive its
costly lawsuit against the nation's cigarette producers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're disappointed,'' said Peggy Roberts, spokeswoman for
Philip Morris Management Corp., parent company of Philip Morris
U.S.A., the nation's biggest cigarette maker.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said the Clinton administration ''can't get enough out
of the taxes we pay, and it's totally politically motivated to
punish us.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts' comments came after the House voted, 215-183, Friday to
let the Justice Department tap three other agencies for $12 million
next year to help pay for the litigation. Attorney General Janet
Reno has said that without the extra money she would have to drop
the legal action, which could net billions for the government,
because her department could not afford it.
</P>
<P>
   After the roll call, President Clinton said the House had
''voted decisively to support the interests of the American people
over those of the special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   But tobacco supporters in the House thought otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the way to promote the administration's political
agenda,'' said Rep. Robin Hayes, R-N.C. He said Clinton's effort to
raise cigarette taxes by 55 cents a pack didn't work, ''so he comes
in the backdoor with a lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks to recover an unspecified amount of money to
help cover the more than $20 billion that officials say the
government spends every year to care for millions of veterans,
senior citizens, and others with tobacco-related health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Still-unwritten Senate legislation might also contain language
denying the Justice Department the extra money. But the House vote,
along with a White House veto threat, would make its fate shaky.
</P>
<P>
   Joining 159 Democrats in voting for the extra money were 55
Republicans, largely from northern states and California. Voting
''no'' were 147 Republicans plus 35 Democrats, mostly from tobacco
growing regions. The House's two independents split.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy lobbying pitted cigarette makers against health, veterans,
senior citizens and other groups.
</P>
<P>
   The vote capped a topsy-turvy week that began when the House
voted 207-197 on Monday against letting the Justice Department
accept $4 million from veterans' health programs to pay for the
litigation. A day later, the House voted by voice to let the money
come instead from the Department of Veterans Affairs'
administrative budget.
</P>
<P>
   The pivotal difference was 25 Republicans, mostly from the North
and California, who voted ''no'' on Monday but ''yes'' on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was taking out of veterans'' in Monday's vote, Rep. Ralph
Regula, R-Ohio, one of the switchers, said in an interview. ''And
this vote wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's roll call was one of the few failures the tobacco
industry has suffered on Capitol Hill in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco allies scuttled the Senate's 1998 effort to levy $516
billion in new taxes on the industry and use the money for health
and anti-smoking programs. They also have resisted recent Clinton
proposals to boost the cigarette tax, and stymied efforts to let
the federal Food and Drug Administration regulate tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Following the $246 billion settlement the states reached with
tobacco companies in 1998, the Justice Department filed its own
lawsuit last September.
</P>
<P>
   The legal action is expected to cost the department $40 million
this year and next. To help defray it, the administration would let
the Defense, Veterans Affairs and Health and Human Services
departments each contribute $4 million to Justice next year.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4690.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   House Appropriations Committee Republicans:
http://www.house.gov/appropriations/
</P>
<P>
   House Appropriations Committee Democrats:
http://www.house.gov/appropriations--democrats/
</P>
</TEXT>
