<HEADLINE> Gore Continues With Fund-Raisers  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE GLOVER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore held his head as he
heard Democratic financial heavyweight Water Shorenstein label
rival George W. Bush a ''lightweight, shortsighted hypocrite,'' a
comment that was rather sharp even if it did draw a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lighter moment as Gore determinedly worked his way
through a long list of high-dollar gatherings throughout the West,
even as new controversy was raging over his financial dealings in
the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore raised just over $1.1 million in a couple of fund-raisers
in Denver, before heading to northern California where he pulled in
an additional $1.5 million, $1 million of it at a San Francisco
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   All of it is ''soft money'' that will go to the Democratic
National Committee but would be eliminated under campaign finance
overhaul proposals Gore argues would be at the top of his list if
he's elected.
</P>
<P>
   He never fails to note that, even when supporters are shelling
out $25,000 apiece to rub shoulders with him.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're here at a fund-raiser and I'm grateful to all of you for
being a part of it, but I want you to know that part of my agenda,
indeed the first bill that I will send to the United States
Congress as president is the McCain-Feingold campaign reform
measure,'' Gore said at a San Francisco reception.
</P>
<P>
   It's an occasionally awkward scene with Gore at top-dollar
dinners and cocktail parties as controversy swirls around him. A
recommendation has been sent to Attorney General Janet Reno that an
independent counsel be named to look into Gore's fund-raising
practices in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president has rejected that suggestion and on Friday
made public an April 18 interview with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides said they never considered cutting back on the
events, at least until the controversy eases, and said there's
nothing wrong with arguing against soft money while raising a ton
of that cash.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you argue for it on the campaign trail you should argue for
it in these settings,'' said spokesman Chris Lehane. ''Most of
these people who show up at these events believe in it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehane said the current round of money events had been scheduled
for weeks, and scrubbing them wouldn't be fair to the DNC. ''These
have been on the schedule for a long, long time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore routinely argues that backers of campaign finance reform
must live by the rules in place, until they can change the rules.
</P>
<P>
   He made that point in Denver, where donors paid $10,000 each for
a grilled steak and a garlic mashed potato dish. With candles
flickering in an elegant tent, and waiters pouring pricey wines to
local dignitaries Gore forged ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's some irony in me talking about that at a fund-raising
event, but I'm going to do that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
