<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greens Party Backs Nuclear Shutdown  </HEADLINE>
By TONY CZUCZKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Germany's Greens party has endorsed a hard-won
government deal to shut down the nation's 19 nuclear power plants
despite cries of betrayal by many activists who wanted a quicker
phaseout.
</P>
<P>
   The vote Friday at a Greens congress in the western city of
Muenster bolstered the stability of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's
government. The Greens, the junior partner in the 20-month-old
coalition, have pushed for the ''nuclear exit.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder and utility executives agreed last week on a formula
to phase out the nuclear plants by about 2021 -- a deal endorsed by
Environment Minister Juergen Trittin of the Greens even though his
party had wanted the shutdowns to occur at least two years faster.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders, including Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer,
pleaded with delegates to back the deal, insisting the Greens
should take pride in reaching a goal pursued since their founding
two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course we want more. But we won't get more,'' Fischer
shouted in a speech interrupted by jeers and whistles from
hard-line anti-nuclear activists. ''I'm so fed up with this party
always tearing itself down.''
</P>
<P>
   Calls by some Greens for renegotiating the nuclear pullout were
''ridiculous,'' he said, and quibbling about details of the accord
was ''small-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegates voted 433-227 for a proposal by the party leadership
to accept the compromise. Rejection would have cast serious doubt
on the future of the coalition, led by Schroeder's Social
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many delegates objected to the deal, which sets no firm
date for ending nuclear power in Germany and left out Greens
demands for the phaseout to start before the next federal election
in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not a happy end for the anti-nuclear movement, it's more
like a mockery,'' said Undine von Blottnitz, a veteran campaigner
against plans for a national underground nuclear waste dump in
northern Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The largely pragmatic Greens leaders hailed the vote as a sign
of the former protest party's growing political maturity.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, delegates Saturday were to elect two new
party co-chairs and vote on changes in the Greens leadership
structure -- including a candidacy by Fischer for a seat on a new
16-member council to coordinate strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer, a former student radical turned statesman, has long
urged his party to take up new themes and run itself more
professionally, but has never run for party office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 0107 </TRAILER>
