<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Council Ban Prompts Russian Walkout  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council banned Yugoslavia
from participating in a debate on the Balkans, prompting a walkout
by Russia's U.N. ambassador and a bitter debate over Belgrade's
right to be heard when its leader has been indicted for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Before his dramatic exit Friday, Russia's U.N. Ambassador Sergey
Lavrov said ''gagging people's mouths'' set a dangerous precedent
and left the council's meeting without any ''practical meaning''
because a key Balkan player was not represented.
</P>
<P>
   The council's open session on the continuing threats to peace in
the Balkans was further complicated when China's deputy ambassador
walked out as NATO's former secretary-general Javier Solana started
to speak in his current job as the European Union's foreign and
security policy chief.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said Shen Guofang was apparently protesting against
NATO's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade in May 1999
during its bombing campaign to end the Serb crackdown on ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo. Beijing rejects NATO insistence that the
bombing, which killed three Chinese journalists, was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Shen returned after Solana finished. Lavrov did not return. But
both countries filled their council seats with junior diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke urged council members to
exclude Yugoslavia's U.N. envoy Vladislav Jovanovic from the
debate, saying ''he represents a government whose senior leadership
has been indicted for war crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We recommend that the council state clearly and unequivocally
that it rejects the policies of hatred and war espoused by the
Belgrade regime, that it does not tolerate abuses of human rights,
and fully supports the efforts of the war crimes tribunal for
former Yugoslavia to prosecute all -- I repeat all -- of those who
have been indicted,'' Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   But the vote by the 15-member council was hardly unequivocal:
seven in favor of excluding Yugoslavia, four against and four
abstentions.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina's U.N. Ambassador Arnoldo Listre said his abstention
did not imply any support for the Belgrade regime but was based
''on serious doubts'' about the appropriateness of barring
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Lavrov reminded council members that under the U.N.
Charter, even a state that is not a U.N. member has a right to
participate when it is a party to a situation under discussion in
the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ''A very dangerous precedent has thus been created when states
that are unpalatable for political reasons are being isolated from
participation in the work of the United Nations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's envoy has spoken at Security Council meetings both
before and shortly after last year's indictment of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic on war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav envoy Jovanovic called the split vote ''a moral
victory ... and a confirmation that U.S. policy of aggression
against Yugoslavia ... is in conflict with the majority of
countries in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, Holbrooke raised the issue of Yugoslavia's U.N.
membership as another reason for its exclusion. Since 1992 when
four of its six constituent republics declared their independence,
Yugoslavia's membership has been in dispute and it has been
suspended from the General Assembly until its status is cleared.
</P>
<P>
   The procedural vote on Yugoslavia overshadowed the briefing by
Carl Bildt, the special envoy to the Balkans of Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, who warned that if international peacekeeping troops
left the Balkans today, there would ''in all probability be war
tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 0108 </TRAILER>
