<HEADLINE> Mariners 8, Orioles 3  </HEADLINE>
By JIM COUR
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- David Bell hit a two-run homer and Alex Rodriguez
had a two-run double in a four-run fifth inning Friday night as the
Seattle Mariners beat Baltimore 8-3, the Orioles' seventh loss in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   With its fourth straight win, Seattle moved to a season-best 11
games over .500. Baltimore, matching its longest losing streak this
year, fell to a season-worst 11 games below .500.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Meche (4-4) won his fourth straight decision, including
three since coming off the disabled list June 13 because of arm
problems. Scott Erickson (4-4), who may be on the trading block,
lost for the fourth time in five decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 2-0, the Mariners struck for four runs with two out in
the fifth. John Mabry singled and Bell followed with his fourth
homer of the season. Rickey Henderson then walked, Stan Javier
singled, Henderson stole third, and Rodriguez's second double of
the game drove in both runners.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, the Mariners scored four more runs. Tom Lampkin
and Mabry had RBI doubles, Henderson singled in a run and John
Olerud was walked by Cruz Molina with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Conine drove in a run with a single in the fourth and Mike
Bordick had an RBI single in the fifth for Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Meche was taken out with an 8-2 lead after six innings. He gave
up two runs on six hits and a walk, while striking out four.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson was pulled after giving up three hits, two of them
doubles, to open the sixth. He surrendered seven runs on nine hits
and two walks.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. Surhoff had an RBI single in the eighth to extend his
hitting streak to 17 games.
Notes: Orioles 3B Cal Ripken was given the night off by manager
Mike Hargrove because of his sore back. Hargrove used him as his DH
Thursday night. Hargrove said before the game that Ripken, 39, will
play Saturday and Sunday. Ripken underwent back surgery last
September. ... The Orioles, who have baseball's fourth highest
payroll at $81.5 million, have the worst road record in the majors
at 10-29, including seven losses in a row and 12 defeats in 13
games. ... Baltimore is 0-5 at Safeco Field. ... The Mariners sent
nine men to plate in the fifth and 10 in the sixth. ... Rodriguez's
two doubles gave him 39 extra base hits for the season, fifth in
the AL. ... In Baltimore's last 10 games, its starting pitchers are
1-7 with a 10.08 ERA. ... The Mariners signed their 16th pick in
the June draft, OF Jared Jones. Jones is the backup QB at defending
national champion Florida State behind Chris Weinke. Jones is from
Walla Walla (Wash.) HS.
</P>
