<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ringling Circus Has Black Ringmaster  </HEADLINE>
By JAMIE STENGLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- As a little boy in New York,
Johnathan Lee Iverson would make his own costumes, line up a few
friends and put on a show for mom.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson's garb is a little more elaborate these days, his
friends bring animals along and instead of just his mother, ''The
Greatest Show On Earth,'' draws thousands of people each night.
</P>
<P>
   At 24, he is the youngest ringmaster for the Ringling Bros. and
Barnum and Bailey Circus -- and the show's first black man to
introduce children of all ages to the fantasy world of trapeze
artists, wild animals and death-defying feats.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see a big deal about it,'' Iverson said. ''If I were,
like, lime green, I could see the point of it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like performing in anything else -- except your co-workers
are clowns and elephants,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although circuses have long used performers of varying
nationalities, there were rarely blacks under the big top, said
Fred Dahlinger, director of collections and research at the Circus
World Museum in Baraboo, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   ''There have been black perfomers in circus history back to the
1810s, but never in large numbers,'' he said. And even in the
audience, blacks used to be segregated from whites.
</P>
<P>
   Circuses in America date to 1768, Dahlinger said. Early on,
blacks were used as horse riders and animal trainers, but in the
mid-1900s the number of blacks in circuses declined. In the 1960s,
Ringling had troupes of black unicyclists and aerielists, but that
was about it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Philip McKinley, who discovered Iverson at a Wisconsin dinner
theater, said he was looking for a showman; race didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm always moved by talent first, all the rest is secondary,''
said McKinley, who is Ringling's director. ''In the world of the
circus, we're all multicultural anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Dahlinger said, multiculturalism usually refers only to
Europeans and Asians.
</P>
<P>
   ''Blacks are probably the least represented as far as the
numbers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, an Atlanta-based circus founded in 1996
features mostly performers of black and Hispanic descent.
UniverSoul Circus spokeswoman Paula Witt said the group wanted
children of color to see performers who look like them.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an urban circus,'' she said. ''It's not your traditional
circus.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson gave his first public performance at age 11 with the
Boys Choir of Harlem. He attended the Fiorello H. La Guardia High
School of Music and Art and Performing Arts in Manhattan (the
''Fame'' school) before heading to Connecticut's Hartt School of
Music, where he graduated in voice.
</P>
<P>
   McKinley discovered Iverson in Fort Atkinson, Wis., where
McKinley was directing a dinner theater Christmas show during the
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't think I'd be good at it, because I didn't think I was
the 'Ladies and Gentlemen type,''' Iverson said.
</P>
<P>
   But McKinley saw how Iverson, who stands at 6-foot-3, would fit
into the spangling red vest and black topcoat that marks him as the
leader of the show.
</P>
<P>
   ''When he walked in the door I knew there was something special
about him,'' McKinley said. ''The first thing I noticed about him
was his manner, then he opened his mouth and sang and it was
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinley had his proof at Iverson's first rehearsal with the
circus: the sound of Iverson's voice brought the practice to a
halt.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even the animals stopped and were listening,'' McKinley said.
''It was just kind of a peaceable kingdom moment that's frozen in
my mind.
</P>
<P>
   ''The company came onto the floor and stopped and applauded,''
he said. ''That doesn't happen in the circus.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson is in his second full year as ringmaster and has signed
on for another stint as ''the fantasy guy ... who guides you into
this big fantasy world.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't say 'The Greatest Show on Earth' as a catchphrase,''
he said. ''That's why people come. Where else are you going to find
greatness for 10 bucks?''
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Iverson, a postal worker from New York, said her son was
an entertainer from the moment he was born.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a natural gift of his,'' she said. ''He would dress up as
some type of performer and put on a show. He would say, 'Mommy, I
have to perform.'''
</P>
<P>
   When her son was 7, he asked for money to go to the newsstand
and instead of a comic book, he returned clutching a show business
paper with advertisements for actors.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said, 'See Mom, they want actors, you should sign me up,'''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   On March 26, 1999, when the circus was in New York, Iverson's
father, a fireman, died of a heart attack just three hours before
he was set to see his son perform.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't tell him till after the show,'' his mother said.
Iverson stayed with the circus after hearing the news.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said, 'The show has to go on.'''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Ringling Bros. and Barnum and Bailey Circus:
http://www.ringling.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 0141 </TRAILER>
