<DOCNO> APW20000624.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Poll Watchers Abducted  </HEADLINE>
By RAVI NESSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- For the first time since independence,
Zimbabweans are faced with a real opportunity to change the face of
their government when they cast votes in two-day parliamentary
elections beginning Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But after months of political violence and intimidation, many of
the country's 5.1 million registered voters may fear ruling party
retribution if they vote for the opposition -- or if they vote at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ''Zimbabweans are really torn between hope and fear,'' said
Alfred Nhema, head of the political science department at the
University of Zimbabwe at Harare.
</P>
<P>
   The polls opened Saturday morning with lines of 50-100 people
waiting outside several voting sites. First results were expected
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With the economy suffering its worst economic crisis ever,
conditions were ripe for the first serious challenge to President
Robert Mugabe's ruling Zimbabwe African National Union Patriotic
Front party since it led the country to independence from
white-minority rule in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Though the 9-month-old opposition Movement for Democratic Change
has never been tested in an election, a recent poll showed them
winning 70 of the 120 seats being contested. But the party would
need at least 76 seats to have a majority, because Mugabe appoints
the remaining 30 seats in the 150-member parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe, whose term lasts two more years, is not on the ballot.
But the opposition tapped into strong voter anger with Mugabe when
it helped successfully campaign for the defeat of a February
referendum on a new constitution supported by the ruling party --
the party's first electoral defeat ever.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, more than 30 people have been killed and thousands
more injured in a wave of political violence that has been blamed
largely on ruling party militants. Many opposition candidates
campaigned surreptitiously for fear of retribution. Others fled
their districts altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups and opposition politicians worry about the
effectiveness of a campaign they say was largely intended to
frighten opposition supporters from going to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ''Already it's been unfair ... because the method of campaigning
has been so ruthless,'' said Koomalo Zwelithin, a 25-year-old
English teacher at Gloag middle school, about 200 miles southwest
of Harare, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its campaign, the government has held back teachers'
annual raises until after the election, Zwelithin said. But the
promise of a paltry salary increase will not affect his vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''All we're interested in is democracy. We want political
change, not just hazy economic change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This defiant attitude manifested itself in small ways through
the waning days of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The letters MDC were chalked on streets and painted on signposts
throughout the countryside. A guard at the State House
surreptitiously reciprocated when a young boy flashed him the
open-palm symbol of the MDC.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Schori, the leader of the European Union's 173-person
observer mission here, said Friday that he considered turnout the
most important factor in the election.
</P>
<P>
   In the last parliamentary election, in 1995, only 29 percent of
voters cast ballots. But that was a different era, when the country
had no serious alternative to Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
   The political situation in the country has undergone a near
revolution since then, Nhema said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the past there was this mentality of boycotting the
elections,'' Nhema said. Now, ''people are excited about being
given an alternative voice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 0235 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000624.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 02:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Politicians Make Last Appeal  </HEADLINE>
By GARY SCHAEFER
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori made his final appeal
to voters Saturday before lower house elections, presenting his
three-party ruling coalition as a bastion of stability that would
power the economy into recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-day campaign before Sunday's vote to fill the 480 seats
in Japan's more powerful lower house of parliament has focused on
competing proposals for mending the troubled economy.
</P>
<P>
   Mori, head of the Liberal Democratic Party, has pushed hard on
the theme of stability. The government's two-year effort to jog the
economy out of the doldrums with massive fiscal spending is slowly
starting to show results.
</P>
<P>
   Electing the fractured opposition would put those gains in
jeopardy, Mori said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only choice is the coalition,'' he said during a campaign
stop in Yokohama, outside Tokyo. ''When political alliances come
and go, it's the people who end up suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeal appeared to be working. Recent polls suggested the
LDP was set to retain its grip on power, which it has relinquished
only briefly in the last 45 years. Newspapers show the LDP winning
241 to 263 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those numbers, there were some wild cards that could tip
the balance. A large chunk of voters was undecided in the approach
to the election, and surveys suggested turnout would be high --
meaning a larger anti-government vote.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition has focused on the downside of the government's
spending campaign: the ballooning public debt, which now totals
more than 130 percent of the country's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   The LDP wants to continue spending until the economy is firmly
in recovery, then start worrying about the deficit. The biggest
opposition party, the Democrats, however, are calling for a tax
increase to shore up the country's finances.
</P>
<P>
   Yukio Hatoyama, leader of the Democrats, urged Japanese while
campaigning near Osaka, western Japan, to vote for change.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want people to stand up and make their voices heard by
casting a vote,'' he was quoted as saying by Kyodo News agency.
</P>
<P>
   Mori also suffers from sinking support ratings for his Cabinet,
and has stirred controversy with several verbal gaffes.
</P>
<P>
   He was forced to apologize last month after he called Japan a
''divine country centered on the emperor'', conjuring up memories
of Japan's wartime emperor-worship. Mori came under fire days ago
for saying that undecided voters should stay home on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Mori's mistakes have provided ammunition for the divided
opposition parties, which agree on little more than disagreeing
with the government. But the opposition's lack of unity is also a
liability.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' proposal to cut public debt by lowering the
minimum tax bracket may not win many votes, Keiko Higuchi, a
professor at Tokyo Kasei University, said Saturday on Nippon TV.
</P>
<P>
   ''To ask people to take bitter medicine, you have to be a doctor
they can trust,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Japanese also were disappointed that other issues received
little or no attention from candidates. The national Mainichi
newspaper, for example, said the financially troubled national
insurance system had been largely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The vote follows two months of political turmoil. Mori took over
on April 5 after then-Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi suffered a stroke
and fell into a coma. Obuchi died on May 14, and the government was
widely criticized for delays in announcing his illness to the
nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
