<HEADLINE> Despite jump in city reading scores, math numbers barely improve  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - City students improved only slightly on a
citywide mathematics test this year than last, with 67 percent
still failing to meet the Board of Education's standards.
</P>
<P>
   The increase of about one percentage point for third, fifth,
sixth and seventh graders contrasted sharply with the jump in
reading scores - more than five percentage points - released two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Schools Chancellor Harold O. Levy issued a brief written
statement Friday in which he called the results ''disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the first year New York City adopted the state's method
of scoring and reporting standardized tests. The scoring is now
based on whether students achieve proficiency in the skills
demanded by the new state and city learning standards, rather than
on how city students compare with a fluctuating national average.
</P>
<P>
   Scores on the tests are grouped into four levels. On this year's
tests, which were taken in May, roughly 7,000 fewer students scored
in the lowest level than in 1999. The percentage of students in
that lowest level dropped to 30.8 percent, from 33.9 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
   While all of the city's 32 community districts posted gains on
the citywide reading test this year, only 24 of those districts saw
their math scores improve.
</P>
<P>
   District 26 in Queens posted the highest percentage of passing
students with 71.6 percent meeting the standards. Manhattan's
District 2 had the next best passing rate, with 61.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   District 85 - which is made up of schools taken over by the
chancellor because of poor performance - scored a 12.8 percent
passing rate. The lowest passing percentage for a complete school
district came in Manhattan's District 5, where 13.2 percent of
students met the standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
