<HEADLINE> Asian long-horned beetle is back, this time on the Lower East Side  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - It's back!
</P>
<P>
   The Asian long-horned beetle has reared it's ugly head again,
this time in a lower Manhattan playground.
</P>
<P>
   The insect, which weakens and eventually kills trees, was first
found in Brooklyn in 1996, and turned up last year in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest outbreak, beetles were found in three of 36 trees
in the Luther Gulick playground at Columbia and Delancey streets.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only thing you can do is chop down the tree, chip the wood
into tiny pieces and burn it,'' Parks Commissioner Henry Stern said
Friday. Stern sad the beetle has not been detected in Central Park,
but warned that more outbreaks were likely.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four years, more than 2,600 infested trees in
Brooklyn, Queens and upper Manhattan have been chopped down.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said early detection had helped contain the beetle.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are trying to prevent the spread of disease,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bug burrows holes into the bark of trees, laying eggs in the
holes. The hatched larvae then burrow deeper, into the heartwood of
trees. When they reach adulthood, the beetles then dig there way
back out through the tree. Trees weaken and eventually die from
infestation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
