<HEADLINE> Man lunges at police officers with ax, gets shot  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - Two police officers alerted to a home
break-in shot and wounded a man they said charged at them wielding
an ax over his head.
</P>
<P>
   ''Apparently, instead of putting the ax down, he brought it up
over his head and lunged toward the officers,'' said police
spokesman Sgt. Joe Sweeney. ''That's when the officers opened
fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Jennis, 40, was in fair condition at a hospital Saturday.
His injuries were not life-threatening. He faces possible weapons,
burglary and menacing charges.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the shooting appeared to be a ''completely
justified'' act of self-defense. It wasn't immediately clear how
many rounds the officers fired.
</P>
<P>
   A man and woman returning Friday evening to a house next-door to
Jennis' told police they found one of the front doors boarded over
and a sign warning that trespassers would be killed.
</P>
<P>
   Jennis then allegedly approached them holding an ax, they said.
Soon afterward, the couple called 911. When the officers showed up,
the confrontation took place outside his neighbors' house.
</P>
<P>
   Jennis has lived on the street since he was young, and neighbors
said his father died about a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   One neighbor, Larry Knickerbocker, recalled Jennis circulating a
petition about five years ago expressing concern that drug dealers
might be moving into the quiet neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was pretty hard to see a neighbor lying there,''
Knickerbocker said in Saturday's Post-Standard newspaper. ''This
was the guy who would snow-blow everybody's driveways in the
winter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
