<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Biopsy technique brings Canadian woman to Bridgeport  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - When Cynthia Blumenthal went for her
annual mammogram in March, it revealed a tiny lump in her left
breast.
</P>
<P>
   The lump was so small, it couldn't be detected with an
ultrasound. Using the mammogram as a guide, Blumenthal's doctor
performed a core needle biopsy, which showed she had cancer.
</P>
<P>
   When she went to see a surgeon near her home in Ottawa, Canada,
he told her she should have a lumpectomy and all the lymph nodes
under her arm removed.
</P>
<P>
   Then her cousin, an oncologist at St. Vincent's Hospital in
Bridgeport, told her she might be able to avoid having all her
nodes removed through a procedure called a sentinel node biopsy - a
relatively new technique that's being embraced by some surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   In the procedure, a radioactive isotope is injected into the
site of the tumor. The isotope then travels to the lymph node where
the tumor would be most likely to have spread. That node, called
the sentinel node, emits a radioactive signal to a Geiger
counter-like probe.
</P>
<P>
   Using the radioactive signal as a guide, the surgeon then
excises the sentinel node, which is examined in the laboratory. If
it is positive for cancer cells, all adjacent nodes are removed.
</P>
<P>
   But for many patients, the node is not cancerous, and the
procedure allows them to avoid removal of all the lymph nodes,
which can cause complications such as fluid retention, stiffness
and numbness in the affected arm.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal was all set to have the procedure done. But when she
asked her doctor about it, he said she would not be able to get it
done quickly in Canada, where it is performed in some teaching
hospitals but is still not widely available.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said it is still in the research stage and that the
surgeons are not comfortable with it yet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if she decided to have the conventional procedure - a full
node dissection - she was told she'd have to wait six weeks in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   So Blumenthal traveled about 500 miles from her home to
Bridgeport, where she had the procedure done at St. Vincent's
Medical Center within one week. Dr. Daniel Passeri, chief of
surgical oncology at St. Vincent's, performed the procedure. He
removed two suspicious nodes, but both tested negative for cancer.
Blumenthal was able to have the lumpectomy and node biopsy done on
an outpatient basis.
</P>
<P>
   ''They wanted to make sure it was localized and that it hadn't
traveled anywhere, and it hadn't,'' said Blumenthal. ''Everything
looks very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Passeri said that in most cases, if cancer has not invaded the
sentinel node, there won't be any cancer cells in any other lymph
nodes either.
</P>
<P>
   But some surgeons are still skeptical about the procedure
because of the potential dangers of missing the spread of cancer to
lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Krag, a professor of surgical oncology at the
University of Vermont who helped pioneer the technique, said much
more study is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just a diagnostic procedure. The fact of the matter is
that conventional surgery of removing the lymph nodes eradicates
cancer nearly 100 percent of the time,'' Krag said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet sentinel node biopsies, which are also done for melanoma
patients, are becoming increasingly common for breast cancer
patients in the United States, according to the American Cancer
Society.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Vincent's, 40 have been done since 1998. At Bridgeport
Hospital, approximately 35 have been done since early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Smith, director of cancer screening for the American
Cancer Society, said the goal of sentinel node biopsies is to avoid
the potential post-surgical risks for breast cancer patients after
lymph nodes are removed, including lymphedema, where the arm gets
progressively bigger and patients lose mobility.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you've managed to do breast conserving therapy and tell the
patient she has outstanding prognosis ... but one arm is quite a
bit bigger than the other, then you've left her with a much more
visible sign of having had breast cancer than even if she's had her
breast removed,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's extremely traumatic and somewhat disabling as well,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, who had the procedure done in April, is now
finishing five weeks of radiation as a prophylactic measure. She
also must have regular checkups with a surgeon for the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
   Her doctor says that because of early detection, her prognosis
is excellent.
</P>
<P>
   ''She probably has a 90 percent cure rate,'' Passeri said.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal has decided to use her experience to urge women to
get regular mammograms. The American Cancer Society and the
American Medical Association recommend that women get annual
mammograms beginning at age 40.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm amazed at the number of women who are my contemporaries
who don't go for mammograms,'' Blumenthal said. ''These are
educated and professional women, but they're not going for
mammograms.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said she also is pushing the medical community in
Canada to give breast cancer treatments a high priority so women
can get procedures done quickly - whether they have a sentinel node
biopsy or a full node dissection.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just the relief that I felt it was going to be done quickly
was enormous,'' Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It could have gone the other way just as easily, I think, but
the key here is early detection. I can't emphasize enough the
importance of women to get mammograms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-24-00 1256 </TRAILER>
