<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State will not file criminal charges against Hartford business leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The city business leader accused of
improperly funneling state loans to his mistress will not face
criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Chief State's Attorney Chris Morano said Friday that he
would not seek an arrest warrant for Arthur Anderson, saying the
evidence did not meet the burden of proof for a criminal
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The decision means negotiations will resume to reach a monetary
settlement between Anderson and state Attorney General Richard
Blumenthal to settle civil allegations of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Morano was considering criminal charges based on a yearlong
investigation by Blumenthal, who found that Anderson had mishandled
state loans and diverted $200,000 in insurance claim money to Doris
Ford, a woman with whom Anderson had a secret relationship.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, Ford borrowed more than $600,000 to buy and
renovate four apartment buildings. The money was lent through the
Capitol Housing Finance Corp., a creation of the Hartford business
community to finance rehabilitation of low-income housing in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's company, Imagineers, was hired by CHFC to administer
the loan program. Anderson resigned last August from his position
as the program's state-appointed chief.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 and 1994, two of Ford's buildings were destroyed by
fire, resulting in more than $200,000 in insurance payoffs.
Blumenthal said Anderson let Ford keep that cash instead of making
sure it went to the state and the CHFC.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said Ford was continually in default on her CHFC
loans.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson also gave Ford more than $500,000 of his own money
between 1994 and 1998 to keep her quiet about their sexual
relationship, Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's great to know the chief state's attorney has cleared
Arthur Anderson of any criminal wrongdoing,'' Anderson's lawyer,
John Droney, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Chief State's Attorney John Bailey disqualified himself from the
case Wednesday, leaving the decision to Morano. Bailey said he had
a potential conflict of interest because his condominium complex is
managed by Imagineers.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal has not taken Anderson to court, but has said he will
if Anderson does not reimburse the state for insurance money that
should have been applied against unpaid state and corporate loans
he arranged for Ford. Blumenthal has said the state should get at
least $200,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
