<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family fights to change VA policy for vets' grave markers  </HEADLINE>
By CAREN BENJAMIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - When Agostino Guzzo died two years ago, his
wife Sandra made what she thought was a simple request to the
Department of Veterans Affairs: give her a grave marker to honor
his military service.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew how much having served meant to him, how much this
country meant to him,'' said Guzzo, whose husband emigrated from
Italy as a boy and joined the Army when he was 19.
</P>
<P>
   But the DVA turned her down, citing a policy dating back to the
Civil War that only allows markers or headstones for veterans in
unmarked graves.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was so surprised,'' said Guzzo, who began a quest with her
family to change the policy and gained a victory last week when the
Senate backed their effort.
</P>
<P>
   The department will give a headstone or grave marker with a
veteran's name, dates of birth and death, and military branch
affiliation to the family of any eligible veteran in an unmarked
grave in any cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Guzzo, who lived in West Hartford, Conn., and died at age 70 in
April 1998, was not eligible because he was encrypted in a
mausoleum that included his name.
</P>
<P>
   After the DVA turned down the family's request, Guzzo's son Tom
started writing letters to anyone he could think of.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got on the Internet, I talked to anyone who would talk to
me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1998 he spoke with Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.,
who promised to help if he was assured the bill would benefit more
than one family.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd learned the Guzzos were not a special case.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are people like them all across the country who should
be able to place their fathers, brothers and uncles in final
resting places with a clear indication they served their country.
It's the least we can do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd took on the cause but the process moved slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Guzzo pushed on, once driving to meet Sen. Joseph Lieberman,
D-Conn., face-to-face to get his promise of support.
</P>
<P>
   The measure passed as an amendment to the Senate's version of
the Department of Defense Authorization Bill but still must be
squared with the House plan, which does not contain the grave
marker provision.
</P>
<P>
   The DVA has expressed some reservations about the bill, though
in general supports it.
</P>
<P>
   ''In our experience, the requirement that a veteran's grave be
unmarked is, as a practical matter, difficult to enforce and easily
circumvented,'' the department's Assistant Secretary Dennis Duffy
wrote to Senate Veterans Affairs Committee Chairman Arlen Specter,
R-Penn.
</P>
<P>
   For example, families of veterans will request the markers, then
furnish their own headstone as well, Duffy said. Department rules
prohibit ''double-marked'' graves.
</P>
<P>
   The DVA opposes a section of the bill that would make it
retroactive out of concern that would overwhelm the agency's
resources. The department also opposes a provision that would allow
a marker to be placed somewhere other than a graveyard, saying it
is inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   So Sandra Guzzo waits. She has tried to hang an American flag on
her husband's mausoleum but was told by the cemetery to take it
down.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, she wrote a letter to her husband of 40 years
that was read at his funeral. She believes it explains why it is
important for her to get the marker.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tried to bring out what it was all about, why he was even
put on this earth, what he accomplished and didn't accomplish, just
reflecting on his life,'' she said. ''But now he's gone and this
one thing, a thing I think is very significant, is still not
finished.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.cem.va.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-24-00 1257 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000624.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soggy spring a blessing for TPC at River Highlands  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA TOMMELLEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. (AP) - The soggy spring has made the greens
greener and the rough rougher at the TPC at River Highlands, and
conditions couldn't be better for the Greater Hartford Open, said
course superintendent Tom DeGrandi.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.8 million tournament, sponsored by Canon, tees off
Thursday. Pretournament activities begin Monday.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a year makes.
</P>
<P>
   DeGrandi and his 34-member grounds crew had to contend with the
drought of '99 to get the course ready in time for last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had guys who had webbed feet by the end of the year, because
that's all they did was water,'' he said Friday as staff put the
finishing touches on the course. ''We almost ran out of water. This
year we spent all of our time cutting grass. It's really been a
perfect year as far as water goes.''
</P>
<P>
   About a 6&AMP;frac12; inches of rain fell in the first three weeks of June,
well above the average of 3&AMP;frac34; inches.
</P>
<P>
   That's makes it easy for DeGrandi, but tough for the pros. The
3&AMP;frac12;-inch rough sports a healthy, thick mixture of blue fescue and
ryegrass.
</P>
<P>
   ''The biggest impact on the players is our density of rough,''
said DeGrandi. ''I think they're going to be very pleased with the
appearances, and those who miss the fairways, challenged to do what
they need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The field won't include Tiger Woods, but has drawn the man who
beat him earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Sutton won the Tournament Players Championship in March,
outdueling Woods down the stretch at TPC at Saw Grass in Ponte
Vedra Beach, Fla. He also led the Americans to the 1999 Ryder Cup
victory with his 3-1-1 match record.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Geiberger will try to become the first back-to-back
champion. The GHO was his first and only win on tour and he did it
in record style, setting 54 and 72 hole marks in a three-stroke
victory over Skip Kendall last year.
</P>
<P>
   The field also includes Davis Love III, Fuzzy Zoeller, Mark
Calcavecchia, Justin Leonard, Paul Azinger, Steve Jones, Billy
Andrade and Scott Hoch.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the tournament also plays into optimal conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ''In New England, it doesn't get any better than the third week
of June,'' said DeGrandi, a Manchester resident.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament turns into a 24-hour job for DeGrandi, overseeing
his fourth GHO.
</P>
<P>
   ''During the tournament, I sleep here. No sense going home,'' he
said. ''My wife bought me a really cool inflatable mattress.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't mind the inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have the best job in the world,'' he told a reporter while
standing on the sunlit putting green. ''Right now, you and I are
standing in my office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
