<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Measure aims to keep troubled moms from abandoning babies  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The infant girl was found alive and crying
inside a plastic bag in New Brunswick last year.
</P>
<P>
   The baby boy, bundled in blankets, was left in a car seat in a
Sears parking lot in Hackensack in February.
</P>
<P>
   The newborn boy, wrapped in a red T-shirt, was abandoned last
October on the doorstep of a Camden home.
</P>
<P>
   These babies lived. Others die.
</P>
<P>
   A newborn boy was found on New Year's Day, lying amid litter
near Paterson railroad tracks. He later died.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps the best-known case was the infant who died in 1996
after North Jersey teen couple Amy Grossberg and Brian Peterson
threw him into a trash bin outside a Delaware motel.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, five babies have been abandoned in New Jersey,
according to Andy Williams, spokesman for the state Division of
Youth and Family Services.
</P>
<P>
   The little boy in Paterson was the only one to die.
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers are hoping to prevent mothers from abandoning
their newborns with a ''Safe Haven'' bill that passed legislative
committees in both houses last week. Gov. Christie Whitman's staff
said Friday she supports the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Part public relations, part changes to current law, the bill
would make it unlikely that parents who safely deliver an unwanted
child to a hospital or police station would be prosecuted. Instead,
they could simply leave an infant younger than 30 days old and walk
away - no questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, a parent could be charged with endangering the
welfare of a child, a second-degree offense that carries a penalty
of up to 10 years in prison, said Chuck Davis, spokesman for the
state division of Law and Public Safety.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, many of these parents are never prosecuted - unless
they harm the baby or the baby suffers injuries from being
abandoned, said John B. Dangler, Morris County prosecutor and
president of the County Prosecutors Association of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the child's safe and in good health, I don't see anybody's
going to pursue criminal prosecution,'' Dangler said. ''DYFS would
get involved and may take steps to terminate the parental rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The most high-profile child abandonment cases usually involve
babies who die, such as the Grossberg baby. But other children are
quietly abandoned and found before any harm comes to them.
</P>
<P>
   Child advocates and bill sponsors say the measure will send a
message to desperate mothers that they can relinquish a child in a
safe place.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most baby abandonments occur when a mother feels she has no
place to turn,'' said Marie Tasy, director of New Jersey Right to
Life. ''They act out of panic, desperation and fear. They have
often tried to hide the pregnancy. This bill will offer them an
alternative to baby abandonment, without fear of prosecution, as
long as they leave them in a safe place.''
</P>
<P>
   To work, the bill has to be publicized, child advocates say. So
the measure would earmark $500,000 for a 24-hour hotline where
callers could get information about the Safe Haven law and
adoption. The measure also calls for a public education campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more recent cases of child abandonment in New Jersey
involved a Paterson mother of five.
</P>
<P>
   One cold February night, Michelle Booker took her newest baby
and four other children - ages 1, 2, 3 and 4 - to McDonald's for
dinner, according to published reports. Then, she drove the kids to
a Hackensack shopping center where she spent $86.15 on warm clothes
and other necessities for the infant.
</P>
<P>
   She put her newest baby in a car seat in the Sears parking lot,
in a place where someone would quickly find him. Then, she watched
from her car until someone discovered the boy, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A secretary, Booker was charged with child endangerment. She was
released on her own recognizance, but could face a possible 10-year
prison sentence. Bergen County prosecutors say they plan to pursue
the case.
</P>
<P>
   ''She allegedly left a baby in a parking lot in the middle of
winter at 9 o'clock at night,'' said Patricia Baglivi, assistant
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports, the father of all five children had
married another woman and was not helping Booker raise the
children.
</P>
<P>
   Ceil Zalkind, associate director of the Association for Children
of New Jersey, said it is uncertain if the bill would help mothers
like Booker.
</P>
<P>
   ''People who abandon children are desperate,'' said Zalkind.
''They're certainly not thinking about options, and I'm not sure
that having this option means they would use it. But if someone
does take advantage of it, it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill co-sponsor Assemblywoman Charlotte Vandervalk, R-Bergen,
said the measure would not shield a parent who hurts a child. She
expects the bill to pass both houses before the Legislature starts
its summer recess at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   ''The key point is that it offers the mother anonymity,'' she
added. ''We're hoping that by saying the mother's name will not be
released that will motivate some mothers to turn the baby over
alive and safe, as opposed to just throwing the baby away.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman spokeswoman Jayne O'Connor said the governor endorses
the concept but may seek some delay in the law.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have some technical amendments that we are working out with
the Legislature,'' O'Connor said. ''The governor is in agreement
that we have to do something more to address the problem of
abandoned babies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
