<HEADLINE> Greens Party Elects 2 New Leaders  </HEADLINE>
By BURT HERMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Germany's environmentalist Greens party on
Saturday elected two new co-leaders who have the backing of Foreign
Minister Joschka Fischer, a move to further professionalize the
protest party serving in its first-ever national government.
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, Fischer, a prominent Greens member and one of
Germany's most popular politicians, ran for a party post for the
first time. He won a seat on a new 16-member strategy council,
giving him a platform from which to urge the Greens to become a
more effective political force.
</P>
<P>
   The new Greens co-leaders are Renate Kuenast and Fritz Kuhn,
both 44. They called their win at the party convention in the
western city of Muenster a new beginning for the Greens.
</P>
<P>
   The vote comes on the heels of the party's approval Friday of a
deal to shut down Germany's 19 nuclear plants by about 2021. The
issue had been one of the party's main goals since its founding
more than two decades ago, and the new leadership is expected to
set new objectives for the Greens in their governing coalition with
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's Social Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now we must find ourselves and reinvent ourselves without
losing ourselves,'' Fischer told party members.
</P>
<P>
   Said Kuhn: ''We must make clear that we aren't simply the
radical version of the Social Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   The two new Greens leaders face the task of bringing together
the more radical elements of the party -- who had threatened to
reject the nuclear plant deal because it didn't live up to the
party's original demands -- and the more practical-minded wing
prodded by Fischer to become an organized political force.
</P>
<P>
   Kuhn is considered a close confidant of Fischer and is one of
the party's leading strategists and experts on economic issues. He
has said he wanted the Greens to become the ''social-ecological
modernization party,'' and that ecological projects shouldn't have
to mean lost profits for companies.
</P>
<P>
   Kuenast's political orientation is a little more to the left -- a
likely asset in dealing with that branch of the party. She has led
the Greens faction in Berlin's city government and was on the team
that negotiated the coalition agreement between the Greens and
Social Democrats after the 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
   The two are seen as stronger leaders than the two previous party
heads -- Antje Radcke and Gunda Roestel, who didn't run for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   The Greens have come under increasing pressure to deliver after
losses in last month's state elections in North Rhine-Westphalia,
Germany's most populous state, where they dropped from 10 percent
to 7.1 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
