<HEADLINE> Muslim Rebels Release Hostage  </HEADLINE>
By PAT ROQUE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOLO, Philippines (AP) -- Muslim rebels released one of 21 mostly
foreign hostages they have been holding in the southern Philippines
for two months, an official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Aventajado, the government's chief negotiator, identified
the Malaysian man as Zulkurmain Bin Hashim, 29. Authorities were
planning to take him Saturday night to Manila.
</P>
<P>
   Aventajado said no ransom was paid, adding that the release was
''a gesture of goodwill'' by the Muslim separatist Abu Sayyaf
group.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are still holding three Germans, two French, two
Finns, two South Africans, a Lebanese, eight other Malaysians and
two Filipinos they seized April 23 from the Malaysian diving resort
of Sipadan. The rebels brought them to the southern Philippine
island of Jolo, an hour away from the resort.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf is the smaller, but more violent, of two Muslim
rebel groups battling Manila to set up a separate Islamic nation in
the impoverished southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, presidential Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora
said negotiators would offer the Abu Sayyaf government projects
instead of ransom.
</P>
<P>
   The government has a policy of not paying ransom to kidnappers.
On Monday, Zamora said the Abu Sayyaf rebels have demanded at least
$1 million for each captive but he stressed that the government
would stick to its policy.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the Malaysian was the biggest break so far in the
two-month hostage crisis that has brought international attention
to the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations appeared to have soured two weeks ago after the
rebels separated their Caucasian captives from the Asians because
of fears of a military rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Aventajado said he was informed that the rebels
have reunited the hostages in one camp in the Talipao area of Jolo.
</P>
<P>
   In previous meetings with negotiators, the rebels have focused
on political demands, including a separate Islamic state,
protection of traditional fishing grounds from large trawlers --
many of which are foreign-owned -- and the formation of a commission
to examine the problems of Filipino Muslims living in neighboring
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Former Libyan ambassador Ashad Abdul Rajab Azzarouq, one of the
government negotiators, said the rebels have welcomed an offer from
a private Libyan foundation to put up schools, hospitals and work
projects in Jolo.
</P>
<P>
   Still, government representatives have said, on condition of
anonymity, that at least two of five Abu Sayyaf commanders are
interested primarily in a big ransom.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders, Galib Andang, known as Commander Robot, and
Mujib Susukan, control the hostages on Jolo, an impoverished
predominantly Muslim island of 500,000 people about 590 miles south
of Manila.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the hostages have fallen ill, though doctors have
brought medicine and food.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in General Santos, a major southern Philippine city,
a series of bomb explosions killed one woman and injured 37 other
people Saturday. Seven bombs exploded within a span of 20 minutes
outside commercial establishments, including a hotel and three
banks, said regional police chief Manuel Raval.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody claimed responsibility for the bombings, but Raval blamed
the Moro Islamic Liberation Front, the larger Muslim separatist
group.
</P>
<P>
   The bombings came a day after the military captured a major MILF
camp straddling Maguindanao and North Cotabato provinces north of
General Santos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 1341 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000624.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> For Use AMs Sunday, June 25, and Thereafter  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE WATSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTHAMPTON BEACH, N.Y. (AP) - Lt. Col. Graham Buschor narrates
a story with the same thirst for detail he needs for mapping out
treacherous helicopter rescue missions - the kind that he and his
fellow Air National Guardsmen hunger for and like to call
''sporty.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard - this is what we do for a living,'' Buschor, 38,
said haltingly. ''Like I've said before, we're not that special.
We're your neighbors, your friends, the people you pass on the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not heroes''
</P>
<P>
   But these ''non-heroes'' from the 106th Rescue Wing of the New
York Air National Guard - who have operated for years in virtual
anonymity out of a tiny airfield in Westhampton Beach - are on the
verge of stardom. The highly anticipated film ''The Perfect Storm''
premieres Friday, recounting the true tale based on the
best-selling book of the same title that documented the wicked
marriage of storms that rocked the East Coast in 1991, leaving a
trail of death and destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The unit, home to some 850 full- and part-time Air National
Guard members, may have received more attention in previous weeks
than at any time in its history, including the unit's searches for
the remains of TWA Flight 800 and John F. Kennedy Jr.'s private
jet.
</P>
<P>
   Once the media buzz hyping the unit as supermen settles down,
life will return to normal at the base. The pilots and parajumpers
- who make up part of an elite combat rescue team - can go back to
their everyday lives as the Clark Kents of the rescue world.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a group of weekend warriors. A quarter are full-time
Guard members, and many part-timers spend at least a day per week
at the base, some as much as 130 days a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We train and train and train,'' Buschor said. ''It gets
boring, but it becomes apparent why you do it when you're on a
mission.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 287 civilians owe their lives to the 106th since 1975,
and that doesn't count saves made in combat. When the United States
becomes embroiled in conflicts, the squad flies its HH-60 Pave Hawk
helicopters and an accompanying C-130 refueling plane into enemy
territory to pluck downed fighter pilots from enemy soil.
</P>
<P>
   Most people living on Long Island have little knowledge of this
hidden gem. Actually, many in the military don't know either.
</P>
<P>
   ''I sort of stumbled onto the base.... I'm from Long Island - I
had no clue it was here,'' said Lt. Col. Mike Canders, a
44-year-old helicopter pilot with the squad.''
</P>
<P>
   So where did they come from? The base began as a flying club and
became the 394th Bomb Group during World War II. Pilots from the
394th received a French medal, the Croix de Guerre with Palm, for
participating in the Normandy invasion. During the Cold War,
parajumpers (better known as PJs) were dropped behind enemy lines
to take photographs of key locations.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it's one of three Air National Guard units conducting
civilian rescues; the others are in California and Alaska.
Generally, the Coast Guard does water rescues and forest rangers
handle lost mountaineers. The missions too extreme for others get
passed to the Air National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, the success of the mission comes down to the PJs.
They are called ''the tip of the spear'' because they focus on the
target and are the first to strike.
</P>
<P>
   The men - under military regulations no women can be PJs -
enroll in a two-year program aptly known as ''Superman
University.''
</P>
<P>
   Within 12 weeks, the original class of about 100 gets pared down
to 10 or 15, all striving to wear a graduate's beloved maroon
beret. Candidates - some of whom already have been Navy Seals or
Army Rangers - are tested to the point of exhaustion, then pushed
still harder. They run and do calisthenics for 20 hours a day, then
sleep for a few precious hours.
</P>
<P>
   But the real testing takes place underwater.
</P>
<P>
   For example, candidates must repeatedly swim 50 meters
underwater. About 30 meters in, an instructor ''harasses'' the
swimmer, grabbing them, pulling on their mask, even striking them.
Swimmers can break the water's surface once during the testing; a
second time and the candidate is ejected from the program.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, swimmers refuse to acknowledge their need to breath.
Eventually, the body tries to protect itself and prevent water from
entering the lungs. That's when an involuntary reflex constricts
their esophagus, knocking them out.
</P>
<P>
   ''You look for a guy like that,'' said PJ Ken Smith, 32.
''That's a sign of mind over matter, of having a strong heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Unconscious swimmers are yanked from the water and resuscitated
with an oxygen tank. They get 10 minutes to recover before they
return to their water tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Once the class is whittled down, the real work begins. PJs spend
several different sessions, usually lasting four weeks, turning
them into highly skilled soldiers. Their primary talents are
jumping from planes - sometimes under extreme conditions like
leaping from 30,000 feet and pulling their ripcord at 3,000 so they
slip under enemy radar - and performing medical procedures, such as
inserting chest tubes or conducting field amputations. They also
train for mountain and deserts rescues.
</P>
<P>
   Graduates are sent to one of the three bases where they extend
their training through repetition and the prodding of cagey vets.
Then they wait for their first mission, which may be a simple
medi-vac from a vessel in the Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   If they are lucky, it's as extreme as Buschor's second-most
famous undertaking, a 15-hour, 1,600-mile adventure off of Nova
Scotia, which set an unofficial record for the longest unplanned
helicopter flight. A freighter sank, putting 30 sailors into the
sea. By the time the helicopter arrived, sharks had killed nearly
all, but the crew saved one man (a second was saved by a passing
ship).
</P>
<P>
   ''It's something special to pick someone up who is in trouble
and bring them back to their families,'' said Canders, who is
credited with 10 ''saves.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the squad's part-timers hold everyday jobs. Some are
cops or correction officers, others are airline pilots or company
executives. Some became doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, they work together, and they play hard together.
Summer barbecues are frequent, and someone is always around to
share a beer. There's also a shoulder to lean on, and people can
spot marital strife, family woes, or just plain depression if the
person doesn't let on soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''The guys I feel closest to are the para-rescuemen out here,''
said Smith, 32, who also is on the New York Police Department's
scuba team. ''We can all share something no one else can.''
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 30, 1991, those bonds were put to a fierce test during
what became known as ''The Perfect Storm,'' a-once-in-a-100-year
nor'easter that forced several ships and boats to issue distress
calls. One was the Andrea Gale, a 75-foot commercial fishing vessel
that eventually sunk, drowning everyone on board.
</P>
<P>
   Author Sebastian Junger focused on the Andrea Gale but also
wrote about a helicopter from the 106th known as Jolly 110, which
was copiloted by Buschor. The crew was returning home at night
after being unable to get a sailor off his boat when the Jolly 110
encountered 100 mile per hour winds that made it impossible to
refuel with the C-130. Realizing that the helicopter wouldn't make
it back, pilot Dave Ruvola decided to ditch and Buschor issued the
mayday call.
</P>
<P>
   PJs Arden ''Rick'' Smith and John Spillane, along with Buschor,
leaped into a sea where some waves reached 100 feet. Ruvola, along
with engineer Jim Mioli, remained onboard to set the aircraft down.
Both then escaped from the sinking helicopter
</P>
<P>
   Buschor wound up on his own. Somehow in the pitch darkness of
night and earsplitting winds, Ruvola, Mioli and Spillane found each
other. They were in bad shape; Spillane had several broken bones
and Mioli was the only one not wearing his survival suit.
</P>
<P>
   ''The wind is howling, you're getting hammered by waves every
few minutes, you're swallowing gallons of water, which makes you
vomit and then get the dry heaves,'' said Buschor. ''I wasn't
confident. The way I looked at it, we were screwed.''
</P>
<P>
   Four hours after going into the ocean, a search plane spotted
Buschor's emergency strobe light. Soon after, a 205-foot Coast
Guard cutter, the Tamaroa, found Buschor being tossed like a toy by
the waves.
</P>
<P>
   Ten Coast Guard crewmen volunteering to stand on the deck,
untethered and holding on for dear life, pulled him aboard once he
latched onto a cargo net, dislocating several of his fingers in the
process. Ruvola, Mioli and Spillane came out about an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, scores of aircraft and ships scoured the ocean but
never found Rick Smith. Many speculate that he and Spillane leaped
from about 70 feet, landing in-between waves because they couldn't
see the turbulent ocean. Unlike Buschor, neither wore night-vision
goggles, which might have enabled them to time their jump and land
on the crest of a wave about 10 feet down.
</P>
<P>
   The death was the first for the unit during a mission. Three
members were killed while training years earlier when a helicopter
flew into a mountain.
</P>
<P>
   An Air Force review of the Jolly 110 mission found the crew
wasn't at fault. Some minor protocol changes were made, but the
main improvement came from technical advances: now pilots can use
the Internet to check weather patterns, when before they waited for
faxes of weather reports.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years later, the 106th has moved on. But a mural on a wall
in the PJs locker room depicting the rescuers' mantra remains a
constant reminder of the past - and the potential future.
</P>
<P>
   The motto?
</P>
<P>
   ''So that others may live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
