<HEADLINE> Parton Tries To Be Mindful of Nature  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIGEON FORGE, Tenn. (AP) -- Country singer Dolly Parton had mixed
feelings at the groundbreaking for a $20 million water park next to
her Dollywood theme park.
</P>
<P>
   Razing of the 35-acre site in Parton's hometown began Friday,
uprooting trees more than a century old.
</P>
<P>
   Parton acknowledged that progress came at a price, but that she
was trying to be sensitive to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ''You always hate to tear up land,'' Parton said. ''But in order
to progress and provide things for people to do, you kind of have
to sacrifice. We are doing whatever we can to save some of these
beautiful trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Parton's transformation from country singer and actress to theme
park impresario has turned her corner of the Great Smoky Mountains
into a tourist mecca of hotels, malls, amusement arcades and
restaurants.
</P>
