<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaping-mules act canceled amid complaints  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LACKAWANNA, N.Y. (AP) - High-diving mules might not be making
much of a splash this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The ''World's Only Hi-Diving Mule'' show, one of the most touted
acts at the Lackawanna Festival in suburban Buffalo, was scrubbed
Friday after organizer Tim Rivers refused to allow veterinarians to
assess his act - which could have led to seizure of the animals by
an animal-protection group.
</P>
<P>
   It's still up in the air whether the show will go on either
Saturday or Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in Erie
County said it has gotten complaints from several hundred residents
about the diving act - in which mules plummet from a deck between
12 and 30 feet high into six feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   Two veterinarians alerted by the group attended the three-day
festival to observe the mules. ''We would have to wait until the
show takes place to determine whether any cruelty is happening or
not,'' the group's spokeswoman, Gina Browning, said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   State law mandates that if cruelty is found, the animals must be
taken from their owner, said the group's executive director,
Barbara Carr. Veterinarians could intervene if they decide that the
force of impact and stress on the animals constituted cruelty, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Festival officials, however, were attempting to bring in state
veterinarians or veterinarians from local racetracks who have
expertise in horses so that the show might take place Saturday or
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until we can get a small panel of vets to make a fair
decision, we'll hold off,'' Angelo Iafello, the city's recreation
director, told the Buffalo News. ''That way everyone will feel more
at peace and comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivers, who owns the Citra, Fla.-based show, said the mules are
not punished for not wanting to dive, are not rewarded for diving
and actually enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   The mule act, however, has landed him in trouble elsewhere. A
1994 statewide injunction prevents him from performing mule-diving
in Illinois.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-24-00 1417 </TRAILER>
