<DOCNO> APW20000624.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> War Correspondents Return to Korea  </HEADLINE>
By SANG-HUN CHOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Correspondents who covered the Korean
War gathered Saturday in Seoul to share their experiences and help
mark the 50th anniversary of the beginning of the three-year
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Invited by the South Korean government, the graying former war
correspondents attended luncheons and visited Inchon and other
famous battle-sites during their weeklong visit. The anniversary is
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Among those participating in Saturday's discussion was retired
Associated Press correspondent Bill Shinn, 81, who scooped the
others by first reporting Gen. Douglas MacArthur's Inchon landing
in September 1950. Also here was Max Desfor, 87, a former AP
photographer who won the Pulitzer prize for his work during the
war. Desfor's picture of refugees crawling across a blown-up bridge
is probably the best-known Korean War picture.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Prendergast, 84, who covered the Korean War as a Time
Magazine correspondent, talked Saturday about his most horrendous
experience of the war: seeing dozens of American POWs who had been
shot to death in cold blood.
</P>
<P>
   Prendergast was following American troops pushing communist
invaders back to the north in the spring of 1951.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were going up the road and an officer came and took us to
the field. There were about 50 American soldiers shot to death by
Chinese or North Korean soldiers,'' said Prendergast, of Trappe,
Md. ''They were all stripped of their clothes. They were completely
naked.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford M. Poats, a 78-year-old former United Press
correspondent, said he was moving with a heavy flow of civilian
refugees ahead of the communist onslaught in July 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Two South Korean military trucks, loaded with crouching
prisoners in white peasant clothes, passed by him and veered off
into the field. In the back of the 2&AMP;frac12;-ton trucks were policemen who
had the muzzles of their rifles on the back of some of the
prisoners. Poats followed the trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard rifle shots. My gosh, they were shooting prisoners in
the truck and then kicked them onto the field. In several cases,
they shot the prisoners and then for some reason hit them with the
butts of their rifles and then threw them out,'' said Poats, of
Falls Church, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Historians say South Korean military police summarily executed
thousands of leftist suspects without trial in the early weeks of
the war for fear they might collaborate with the advancing
communist forces.
</P>
<P>
   Even more gruesome, Poats said, was seeing South Korean officers
shooting to death their own injured men because they lacked medics
or transportation. They feared that the wounded might fall into
enemy hands with vital intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ''You could walk or you were dead. I saw that happening several
times,'' Poats said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Poats and Prendergast saw ''radical differences'' in the
ways that war correspondents covered the Korean War and the Vietnam
War. While American journalists in Vietnam indulged in disclosures,
they were ''part of the team'' with the American troops in Korea by
not reporting anything that could damage the morale of the
soldiers, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of their most vivid memories were how they were called to
duty on June 25, 1950, a Sunday, when North Korea invaded South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Prendergast, then a third secretary at the U.S. Embassy in
Seoul, was tending to the lawn at his Seoul home, one of the old
Japanese-style houses left by the defeated Japanese colonialists at
the end of World War II and used by U.S. embassy staff. His office
called him in.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until he saw South Korean soldiers moving in
trucks holding up tree branches with both hands for camouflage, and
two enemy planes strafing near the embassy and the South Korean
government headquarters, that he realized a war had started. The
U.S. embassy burned all its papers and evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   Prendergast returned home in August. But he came back to Korea
in October 1950 as a Time correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   Poats was playing tennis in Tokyo when his office called him in
that Sunday. After he landed in Korea, Poats said he once wrote a
story and attached the typewritten pages to the legs of two
pigeons, hoping they would carry the copy to his Tokyo UP bureau.
</P>
<P>
   He also intended to ridicule the U.S. military, because it
allowed only one phone line for dozens of journalists and the line
rarely got through.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, the pigeons did not show up in Tokyo. The joke
among the correspondents was that the AP sabotaged them,'' Poats
said, referring to the rival news agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 1417 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000624.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haitian Groups Condemn Election  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL NORTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) -- Haiti's business and religious
groups on Saturday joined opposition parties and the international
community in condemning election results that gave former President
Jean-Bertrand Aristide's party control of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot endorse results that correspond neither to electoral
law nor to generally accepted norms,'' said the declaration
broadcast by 17 organizations, including the Chamber of Commerce,
the Association of Haitian Industrialists, the Roman Catholic
Bishops Conference and the Protestant Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Final results from the May 21 local and legislative elections
were published this week. They showed Aristide's Lavalas Family
party winning 16 of l7 seats in the 27-seat Senate during
first-round balloting and 26 seats in the 83-member House of
Deputies.
</P>
<P>
   Since Lavalas is leading in most lower-house races where a
second round is necessary, the party is likely to control both
houses of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties said they would boycott the second round,
which was postponed indefinitely this week. They have called for
new elections, charging that the vote count was rigged to ensure a
victory that would make Haiti virtually a one-party state.
</P>
<P>
   Aristide is favored to win presidential elections later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations, the Organization of American States, Canada,
France and the United States all have condemned Haiti's method of
calculating first-round Senate winners.
</P>
<P>
   Under Haitian law, candidates must win a majority to avoid a
second round of voting. But officials counted the votes of only the
top four contenders and not the others who ran and may have gotten
a few votes.
</P>
<P>
   Those missing votes created an erroneous winning percentage
count, observers say, giving at least eight of 16 Senate seats to
Aristide candidates who otherwise would have to face a second
round.
</P>
<P>
   French Ambassador Yves Gaudeul warned that international aid
could be reduced or halted as a result.
</P>
<P>
   ''Haitian authorities had better understand we aren't joking,''
said Gaudeul, the top EU representative in the island nation.
</P>
<P>
   Some $100 million in EU aid already is suspended pending a new
Parliament. International creditors have also frozen $400 million --
desperately needed money in this impoverished Caribbean country.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti's Electoral Council has adamantly affirmed its exclusive
right to determine the results, and Lavalas Family spokesman and
Senator-elect Yvon Neptune on Friday called the reaction of the
international community ''a colonial reflex.''
</P>
<P>
   Haiti hasn't had a Parliament since January 1999, when
Aristide's protege, President Rene Preval, dismissed lawmakers to
resolve a power struggle and promised new elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 1420 </TRAILER>
