<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White-Led Parties Ally in S.Africa  </HEADLINE>
By GREG MYRE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- South Africa's two largest
white-led parties announced Saturday they would unite with the aim
of building a stronger opposition to the governing African National
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party and the New National Party, the second and
fourth largest parties in the current parliament, said their union
would be called the Democratic Alliance, the South Africa Press
Association reported.
</P>
<P>
   The two parties share ''the desire to build a political movement
that is home to South Africans from all communities and that will
effectively challenge the ANC for political power.''
</P>
<P>
   However, their combined forces will command only a fraction of
the seats controlled by the dominant ANC.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's parliamentary elections, the Democratic Party won
38 seats and the New National Party captured 28, compared to 266
for the ANC.
</P>
<P>
   Both white-led parties have sought to reach out to the black
majority in South Africa with only limited success.
</P>
<P>
   The New National Party was the successor of the National Party,
which formally introduced apartheid and ruled South Africa for more
than 40 years until the first all-race elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The liberal Democratic Party opposed apartheid during the era of
white rule, and has been able to attract some black support in the
post-apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Leon, the leader of the Democratic Party, will head the new
alliance. Marthinus van Schalkwyk, the head of the New National
Party, will become the deputy leader.
</P>
<P>
   The parties agreed there was an urgent need for opposition
groups to join forces to challenge to the ANC.
</P>
<P>
   However, whites account for only a little over 10 percent of the
population in South Africa, and without strong support from blacks,
the new party will have a limited electoral base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
