<DOCNO> APW20000624.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NJ--Feds-Fowler,620  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) - Federal prosecutors and IRS agents are
investigating possible tax evasion and money laundering charges
against former elections commissioner Jerry Fowler, a newspaper
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler faces trial in November on state charges that he skimmed
payoffs from inflated voting machine contracts.
</P>
<P>
   At least five federal subpoenas have asked for financial
documents related to contracts and companies named in the state
indictment, The Times-Picayune reported, quoting unidentified
sources.
</P>
<P>
   It said the subpoenas are related to Fowler's involvement with
voting-machine contracts and with a Natchitoches yogurt company
that state prosecutors say was used to launder Fowler's share of
alleged kickbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is in its early stages, the newspaper quoted
its sources as saying. It is not uncommon for investigators to
spend more than a year on research before deciding whether to seek
indictments.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said those subpoenaed include Florida businessmen
Ralph Escudero and Glenn Boord, who pleaded guilty in August 1999
to funneling more than $1 million in payoffs between 1992 and 1998
to Fowler and his co-defendant, New Jersey businessman Pasquale
''Pat'' Ricci. Authorities have said Fowler purchased 122,000
voting machine counters over the years from Ricci's Moorestown,
N.J., company, Independent Voting Machine Services.
</P>
<P>
   Escudero and Boord were partners in Uni-lect Inc., a Florida
company that prosecutors say sold voting machines and parts at
inflated prices to the state Elections Department. Prosecutors say
the men often delivered $20,000 bundles of cash to Ricci and Fowler
during secret monthly meetings at hotels, restaurants and airports
in New Orleans and Baton Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoena orders the former Uni-lect owners to deliver
hundreds of documents to special agents of the Internal Revenue
Service's criminal division June 29 in the grand jury room at U.S.
District Court in Baton Rouge. The subpoena asks for all documents
related to the Elections Department, Fowler and Ricci. It also asks
for documents related to Independent Voting Machine Service Co.,
which supplied parts to the Elections Department.
</P>
<P>
   A separate subpoena was sent to the Elections Department, which
released a copy of the subpoena to The Times-Picayune after a
public records request.
</P>
<P>
   The Elections Department's subpoena asks for all records related
to voting-machine purchases and to contracts for hauling the
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Another subpoena requesting financial documents was sent to
lawyers who completed legal filings related to the yogurt company,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler's attorney, Michael Small, said he was aware that some
subpoenas had been sent, but did not know any details about the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors in New Orleans also have explored the Fowler
case, the newspaper quoted its sources as saying. It was not clear
why both the New Orleans and Baton Rouge offices have looked at the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The federal probe of Fowler comes as Small and other defense
attorneys are preparing for pretrial hearings in the state
corruption case.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler is charged with four state counts of felony malfeasance
in office, four of money-laundering conspiracy and one of filing
false public records. The case is scheduled to go to trial Nov. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler lost his re-election bid in November, three months after
his indictment, ending his 20-year hold on a state office that he
took over when his father, Doug Fowler, decided to retire in 1979
after occupying the post for more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler has said he is innocent and has called his indictment ''a
politically motivated character assassination aimed at destroying
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-24-00 1515 </TRAILER>
