<HEADLINE> Switzerland To Try for U.N. Bid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BASEL, Switzerland (AP) -- Switzerland's government will likely
try in 2002 to win voters' approval to join the United Nations,
President Adolf Ogi said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will win,'' Ogi told U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
during a visit to the northwest city of Basel.
</P>
<P>
   Although Switzerland hosts the second U.N. headquarters in
Geneva and belongs to some U.N. agencies, such as the World Health
Organization, the neutral Alpine country has refrained from joining
the full United Nations and is only an observer of the U.N. General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1986 referendum, 75 percent of Swiss voters turned down a
previous initiative to join.
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly will meet next week in Geneva to review the
U.N. global campaign against poverty. The Swiss government paid $3
million to cover the additional cost of holding the session outside
New York, officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
