<HEADLINE> Albright Begins Visit to Poland  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
arrived in Poland's capital Saturday to join foreign ministers from
some 100 countries for discussions on human rights and democratic
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day conference on democracies, to begin Monday, is to
focus on strengthening international institutions and sharing
experiences on how to build enduring democratic structures.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates are also expected to issue a joint declaration at the
end of the conference, which was being sponsored by Poland, the
United States, the Czech Republic, Chile, India and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Before the conference opens, Albright is to travel Sunday to the
Baltic port city of Gdansk -- the birthplace of the Solidarity
movement that led Poles and other East European nations in toppling
communism. There she is to receive an honorary degree from the
Gdansk University in recognition of her contribution to building
democracy in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Gdynia, Albright will join Polish Prime Minister Jerzy
Buzek for a ceremony to name a warship after the 18th century
Polish and American hero, Kazimierz Pulaski. The frigate to bear
Pulaski's name is a gift from the United States to Poland's navy.
</P>
<P>
   Poland, which managed to restore a democratic system after more
than four decades of communist rule, joined NATO last year, along
with Hungary and the Czech Republic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
