<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins Coated in Oil in S.Africa  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- Volunteer workers collected
hundreds of oil-coated penguins and prepared to scrub them clean
Saturday, a day after a tanker sank off Cape Town's coast and
unleashed a large oil slick.
</P>
<P>
   The Panama-registered Treasure went down Friday about six miles
offshore, carrying 1,300 tons of fuel oil and 130,000 tons of iron
ore.
</P>
<P>
   Survey teams reported small dollops of oil rising to the surface
Saturday, and a large slick extending toward nearby Robben Island.
The rocky outcrop, now a nature reserve and home to a large penguin
colony, was previously used by the apartheid government to house
political prisoners, including former President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   As of Saturday afternoon, no oil had reached Cape Town's
beaches, which are among the country's most popular tourist
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   The penguins slathered with oil were being gathered from Robben
Island and mainland beaches to be scrubbed clean at a
rehabilitation center run by the Southern African National
Foundation for the Conservation of Coastal Birds.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation expected to collect up to 1,000 oil-drenched
penguins on Saturday alone. It warned that the spill could have a
devastating effect on the aquatic bird population.
</P>
<P>
   ''The initial oil slick covered their main feeding ground and
most penguins will be swimming through oil to get back to Robben
Island,'' the foundation's Estelle van der Merwe said.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 19,000 penguins on Robben Island, and many more
live along South Africa's coastline.
</P>
<P>
   Officials trying to contain the oil from spreading said there
were some encouraging signs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The flow is not constant and the quantities are not large,''
the South African Maritime Safety Authority said in a statement.
''It is anticipated that the latest reports will confirm the vessel
is still intact.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities hope oil remaining in the Treasure's fuel tanks can
be pumped into another vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Before sinking, the Treasure developed a 17-by-10 yard hole in
the hull -- apparently either from rust or a crack related to its
age.
</P>
<P>
   The ship, heading from China to Brazil, was too large to be
brought into the Cape Town harbor for repairs, and authorities
ordered it towed offshore to reduce the risk of oil pollution.
</P>
<P>
   After two hours under tow in heavy seas, the towrope ripped
loose from the Treasure's deck. The ship then drifted eastward and
sank. All 29 crew members were airlifted to safety.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 1525 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000624.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serb Attack Suspect Said Sheltered  </HEADLINE>
By KATARINA KRATOVAC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A key opposition party in Serbia
accused Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's police Saturday of
sheltering a suspect in last week's attempted murder of the party's
leader.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian Renewal Movement, whose leader Vuk Draskovic was
wounded in a June 15 attack in Montenegro, demanded in a statement
that Milosevic's police ''turn over the terrorists'' wanted by
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The statement followed reports that Dusan Spasojevic, 31, who
has been implicated by Montenegrin police as a third suspect in the
Draskovic shooting, was hospitalized at a Belgrade clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Spasojevic's lawyer, Slobodan Milivojevic, told the Glas
Javnosti daily that his client had intended to travel to Montenegro
to turn himself in, but his health ''suddenly deteriorated'' two
days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Spasojevic, a real estate investor from Belgrade, suffers from
chronic heart disease, the lawyer added. He quoted Spasojevic as
saying he was in Belgrade on the night Draskovic was attacked,
undergoing treatment at a clinic he visits regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Glas Javnosti did not specify at which clinic the suspect was
being treated.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic was grazed by two bullets at his summer home in
Montenegro, Serbia's junior partner in the Yugoslav federation.
According to Montenegrin police, six suspects sneaked up to the
verandah and fired eight .32 caliber bullets at the opposition
leader through a window.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Draskovic has added to the political tensions in
Serbia, where the government has recently launched a major
crackdown against opponents. On Saturday, police prevented an
anti-government gathering by the student-run Otpor, or Resistance,
group in the southern town of Leskovac, detaining six people.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic has accused Milosevic's secret service of being behind
the attack. Montenegrin authorities, who are at odds with
Milosevic's regime in Belgrade, have remained silent on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian Renewal Movement echoed Draskovic's accusations
Saturday, saying that ''stories about sudden heart attacks ...
launched by Belgrade police, are an apparent attempt to protect the
terrorists by those who employed them.''
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic's lawyer, Borivoje Borovic, told Belgrade B2-92 radio
Spasojevic's hospitalization was a ''farce.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Serbian police had an obligation to turn him over,'' he said.
''It is obvious that he enjoys protection by Serbian police.''
</P>
<P>
   After the murder attempt, Montenegrin police detained two
suspects, Milan and Ivan Lovric, who are currently being held in
one-month custody during pretrial court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Police also implicated Spasojevic and a fourth man in the
attack, as well as two unidentified persons. All four were reported
to have fled to Serbia. Montenegrin police have demanded they be
handed over.
</P>
<P>
   The Lovrics, who are cousins, denied in a closed-door hearing
Thursday that they had anything to do with the attack, as well as
any knowledge of Spasojevic and the fourth identified suspect,
their lawyer Nikola Martinovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Spasojevic's attorney told Glas Javnosti his client learned from
media he was a suspect in the Draskovic shooting and ''reported
himself willingly'' to the Belgrade police last week.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper also quoted a Belgrade police press officer, Col.
Mijodrag Gutic, as saying Serbian police were ''at the full
disposal'' of their Montenegrin colleagues and were taking steps to
arrest the fourth known suspect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
