<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Physical Therapists Try To Recoup  </HEADLINE>
By ELIZABETH A. DAVIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Bill Gentile quit his job as a high school
physics teacher to enroll in physical therapy school, fully aware
that the formerly thriving field was in turmoil because of changes
in Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ''I definitely took my time in terms of choosing my next career.
I was weighing several options,'' said Gentile, who will graduate
from the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill in August. ''I
chose physical therapy irregardless of the job market. It was
simply: 'This is really interesting to me.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, attractive starting salaries and an
abundance of jobs made physical therapy one of the most popular and
promising career choices.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, a new limit on Medicare reimbursements threatened
jobs and led to shorter working hours. Unemployment rose and
applications to schools declined.
</P>
<P>
   A slow recovery appears to have begun, helped by a moratorium on
the Medicare limits that took effect in February. Salaries have
remained fairly high, averaging about $56,600 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''At one time, we were touted as the No. 1 job with a seller's
market. Now it is a buyer's market,'' said Jan Richardson,
president of the American Physical Therapy Association and head of
Duke University's physical and occupational therapy department.
</P>
<P>
   About 90,000 physical therapists nationwide work in hospitals,
private clinics, nursing homes and homes. Their patients include
recovering heart attack and stroke victims, surgical patients,
athletes, children with developmental problems or cerebral palsy,
and anyone else needing rehabilitation from injury or disease.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the field peaked in the mid 1990s. Top-notch
students encouraged by career counselors and reports of attractive
starting salaries competed for spots in small bachelor's or
master's programs. They usually had several job offers before
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy new physical therapy programs were accredited after 1995
to meet the demand, and there are 218 today, according to the APTA,
which has since suggested a moratorium on new programs until 2003.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, the Balanced Budget Act for the first time capped
the amount that Medicare could reimburse outpatient facilities for
therapy. A Medicare recipient was allowed only $1,500 a year for
speech and physical therapy, plus $1,500 for occupational therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Work days were shortened for some physical therapists --
especially those in skilled nursing facilities and home health care
agencies -- and salaries dropped.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some patients needing long-term care were denied
placement in nursing homes. Some facilities turned away patients or
had to strictly monitor their care to ensure that Medicare was
covering their costs.
</P>
<P>
   College physical therapy programs were hit hard.
</P>
<P>
   ''When those changes occurred, we saw a very quick response from
applicants,'' said Darlene Sekerak, director of the Division of
Physical Therapy at UNC-Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think everyone has experienced a decrease in applications,''
said Jody Cormack, a therapist and director of clinical education
at the University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Applications for 40 places in UNC's program peaked at 600 in the
mid 1990s, but last year there were 225 and this year only 165,
said Sekerak. USC, however, has been able to fill its 80-person
doctoral program, Cormack said.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Washington in Seattle used to receive seven to
eight applications for each physical therapy class position, but
this year got just four per slot, said the program's director, Mark
Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for therapists, the Medicare cap proved hard to
enforce. Congress placed a two-year moratorium on the cap under the
Balanced Budget Refinement Act that took effect Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The APTA, which only recently began tracking employment
nationally, watched unemployment among therapists jump from 1.2
percent in October 1998 to 3 percent in April 1999 and 3.2 percent
in October 1999. After the moratorium, the rate dipped to 2.9
percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   ''There seems be a swinging of the pendulum already,''
Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of the UNC students who graduated last August
had physical therapy jobs six months later. About one-fourth of
USC's students had job offers before graduation.
</P>
<P>
   ''This year students are finding jobs much quicker,'' Cormack
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gentile is confident he will find a job after he graduates.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is pretty difficult to get a job but, nonetheless, I wanted
to do this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While there may be fewer applicants to schools, ''the folks that
are left really and truly want to be PTs,'' Guthrie said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   American Physical Therapy Association: http://www.apta.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
