<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat in Cairo To Discuss Mideast  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat flew to
Egypt on Saturday from Tunisia, where he had blamed Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak for a lack of progress in the peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat was in Egypt for discussions Sunday with President Hosni
Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
   The essential problem, Egypt's Middle East News Agency quoted
Arafat as saying before leaving Tunisia, ''is Barak's insistence
not to delegate to the Israeli negotiators the necessary mandate
during the talks with the Palestinian side.''
</P>
<P>
   He also cited ''Israel's procrastination in implementing the
signed agreement,'' for a lack of results, MENA reported.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians and Israel have a self-imposed September
deadline for reaching a permanent peace accord, but remain far
apart on key issues such as the status of Jerusalem, borders, and a
return of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's Mideast envoy, Dennis Ross, arrived in the
region Thursday to assess prospects for a Mideast summit in
Washington during which Barak and Arafat would try to formulate the
outlines of a peace treaty. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
was expected to join Ross this week.
</P>
<P>
   A prominent Arab columnist, meanwhile, quoted Arafat on Saturday
as saying he might leave the Palestinian territories for either
Egypt or Tunisia if no agreement is reached with the Israelis soon.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in Al Hayat newspaper, Jihad al-Khazen said Arafat told
him that ''if pressure continues on him, he will head the advice of
his assistants and move to either Cairo or Tunis and leave Barak to
solve his problems with the Palestinians, like Hezbollah.'' The
reference was to Hezbollah guerrillas, who spent decades wearing
down Israel's will to occupy south Lebanon; Israel left last month.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has made similar threats in the past of a Palestinian
revolt against the Israelis if he abandons the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's headquarters were in Tunisia before the Palestine
Liberation Organization moved to Gaza following the 1993 Oslo peace
agreement he signed with then-Israeli Prime Minister Yizhak Rabin.
During his visit, Arafat met with PLO officials in Tunisia and with
the Tunisian president, Zine El Abidine Ben Ali.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
