<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Passenger at Newark Airport dies of meningitis  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Health officials on Saturday were notifying
some passengers who landed here Friday on a flight from Israel that
they might have been exposed to meningococcal meningitis by a
fellow passenger who died after arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were 13 people on the flight that were identified as
sitting in close proximity to the young man,'' Rita Manno,
spokeswoman for the New Jersey Department of Health and Senior
Services, said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   All but one of the 13 - who were from New Jersey, New York,
Pennsylvania and Illinois - had been notified by Saturday afternoon
that they should see a doctor as a precaution and possibly consider
preventive antibiotic therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have no reason to believe that there are any further cases
of meningitis, whatsoever,'' Manno said, terming the notifications
a precautionary measure.
</P>
<P>
   The stricken passenger, Joseph Ferraro, 20, of Rochester, N.Y.,
died at 7:07 p.m. Friday, about two hours after he arrived at
Newark International Airport on El Al flight 17 from Tel Aviv, said
Steve Coleman, a spokesman for the Port Authority of New York and
New Jersey. Port Authority police were notified Ferraro needed help
and took him to Newark Beth Israel Medical Center, where he died,
Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   The El Al jet carried 416 passengers and 19 crew members.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention was notified of
the cause of Ferraro's death, mainly because his fellow travelers
were from multiple states, Manno said. The Port Authority also
notified the New York and New Jersey health departments and other
agencies, and the New Jersey state epidemiologist, Dr. Eddy
Bresnitz, contacted health officials in the other states involved.
</P>
<P>
   Meningococcal meningitis is a bacterial infection of the
membranes around the brain and spinal cord. The symptoms include
fever, neck stiffness and headache.
</P>
<P>
   It is transmitted only through close contact, such as
transmission of saliva through kissing or sharing utensils. Routine
preventive therapy includes treatment with antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no danger to the general public here or to the
passengers on that plane because the contact has to be intimate''
to spread meningitis, Manno said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Ferraro had been on a visit to Israel, apparently on a
group bus tour sponsored by a Jewish youth group. She said the CDC
had identified 89 people on the tour with him, some of whom were
still in Israel and some of whom had returned to the United States,
and was notifying those travelers of the possible risk to them.
</P>
<P>
   Manno said she did not know how Ferraro had contracted
meningitis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
