<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Longtime activist now fights for herself  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL HILL
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - It has come to this for Alice Green: After
decades of working to keep others out of prison, she is fighting to
get herself into prison.
</P>
<P>
   State prison officials have labeled the 56-year-old activist a
security risk and curtailed prison access for Green and her
advocacy group, the Center for Law and Justice. Workers there have
been barred from visiting with groups of inmates. Green - in
typical fashion - is fighting back and speaking out.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here I am,'' she said during a recent interview, ''this
five-foot-two grandmother who somehow or another fomented this
unrest.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Green has been stirring things up for years as one of
the most visible and controversial activists around the state
Capitol. She has fasted on sidewalks. She has told Gov. George
Pataki to stop leading a Martin Luther King Jr. Day parade. She
regularly speaks out on racism and prisoners' rights - sometimes
with caustic language.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sampler from a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   On the prison system: ''We know that prisons are reserved for
people of color.''
</P>
<P>
   On Martin Luther King Day: ''It's not so we have this day set
aside so politicians can exploit his image.''
</P>
<P>
   On race and criminal punishment: ''When any middle-class white
person does something it's poor judgment or indiscretion. When
blacks do it, it's a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Such talk has made Green an irritant to many at the state
Capitol. A New York Post editorial praising her banishment from
prison common areas described Green as an ''obnoxious activist.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, soft spoken in conversation, says it is merely a matter
of fighting for what she believes is right. Her justice center,
created in 1985, counsels people charged with crimes, conducts
educational workshops in minority communities and teaches young
people about their rights and responsibilities. She handles some
3,000 letters from inmates a year, reading them before bed.
</P>
<P>
   Her causes are many, but a common thread is the belief that the
criminal justice system is ravaging minority communities and
families. She sees a vicious cycle - blacks are perceived as
threats and are more apt to be arrested. Once arrested, longer
sentences keep them in the system. And public perceptions harden.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they look at a prison system and they see almost all the
people there are people of color, it affects their perception of
me,'' she says. ''Whether I'm looking for employment or I want to
live next door to you because that image is there - the stereotype
of black people being criminals and dangerous people to live next
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Green was born in a tiny Adirondack town called Witherbee, where
she was the only black girl in her class. She came to Albany in the
'60's as a college student and for the first time began taking part
in anti-war and civil rights demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Green went to school to be a teacher, but later decided she
should get her masters in social work. Her stint as a social worker
convinced her that crime and punishment had a tremendous effect
among the people she worked with. So she went on to get her
doctorate in criminal justice. She is now an adjunct at the
University of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Green has served as legislative director for the New York Civil
Liberties Union and was a deputy commissioner of probation for Gov.
Mario Cuomo. She quit the Cuomo post to protest the
administration's prison-building binge, and has done her criminal
justice work since then on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Dare, president of the Urban League of Northeastern New
York and an admirer of Green's, said: ''There are very few people
who represent those people caught in the criminal justice system,
and represent them well.''
</P>
<P>
   Green garnered wider press attention in 1998 when she ran for
lieutenant governor on the Green Party line, with Al Lewis - aka
''Grandpa'' from ''The Munsters'' television program from the '60s
- heading the ticket. She also has made headlines in a series of
confrontations with Pataki on Martin Luther King Day.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Green persuaded the new governor to give up his
position in the front of the King Day parade. Things got rougher on
King Day '98 when demonstrators, including Green and her husband,
tried to unfurl a banner critical of the governor's prison
policies. Green and her husband were arrested for disorderly
conduct. The charges were later dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Green believes that incident was the beginning of the slow boil
that got her access curtailed from state prisons. A planned visit
to Attica in '98 was canceled suddenly, she says, and an
administrator told her she was a ''radical'' opposed to prisons.
Green told a news conference Wednesday she sensed the governor had
a vendetta against her.
</P>
<P>
   State prison officials say the action was not based on the 1998
incident, but on information indicating Green's group helped
encourage inmates to strike on or around Jan. 1, 2000. There were
fliers circulating among prison inmates late last year urging a
protest of state parole policies and other grievances.
</P>
<P>
   There were no inmate strikes around New Year's Day, although
emergency response teams were stationed near prisons throughout the
state to deal with possible strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections Commissioner Glenn Goord wrote Green a letter in May
saying she and her group posed ''a clear threat to the safety and
security of correctional employees and inmates.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The commissioner's primary responsibility is to make sure that
our people come to work every day and go home to their families and
relatives at night and protect the safety and security of
inmates,'' said Goord's spokesman, James Flateau. ''In the
commissioner's mind, she challenged that.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Goord's decision, Green can still see inmates one-on-one
in prison visiting rooms, but has been denied permission to meet
with groups of inmates in common areas.
</P>
<P>
   Flateau said the law gives the commissioner discretion over who
can make those group visits. Other advocates continue to have group
access to prisons, he said, including critics of the criminal
justice system like Roman Catholic Bishop Howard Hubbard of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ''The line that you do not cross is when you go from advocacy to
inciting,'' Flateau said.
</P>
<P>
   Green strenuously denies that she tried to rile inmates and says
she is not aware of any employees from her center doing so. She
says the ban keeps her from doing important work - prison visits
for legal work, workshops and lectures - and has a chilling effect
on other prison advocates.
</P>
<P>
   She called a news conference Wednesday to say she will continue
to press for a hearing, even though prison officials have told her
she is not entitled to one. She has asked prison officials for a
copy of the evidence against her. She said she will consider a
lawsuit if the ban is not rescinded.
</P>
<P>
   Green admits this comes at a bad time. She has lost so much
ground on issues already - there are more prisons, parole has been
tightened, inmate services have been reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many people say to me 'You've got to be frustrated. It's
getting worse. You have no power.' And they're absolutely right,''
she says. ''But the only alternative is to do nothing, and that I
can't even imagine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
