<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protesters Threaten More Roadblocks  </HEADLINE>
By MELISSA EDDY
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Austrian environmentalists ended their
29-hour blockade of a main mountain highway Saturday but threatened
future roadblocks if new limits are not placed on heavy truck
traffic passing through the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   Since Friday, hundreds of demonstrators had blocked the Brenner
highway, which runs over the Austrian Alps between Germany and
Italy on one of Europe's main north-south routes. The highway was
open for traffic Saturday afternoon after the blockade came to an
end.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, villagers and politicians supported the
protest. It was organized by a group called ''Transitforum Tirol,''
which is demanding that the EU allow Austria to set its own
regulations on how much truck traffic be allowed to use the Brenner
highway. The group accuses the EU of violating existing transit
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz Gurgiser, who heads the Transitforum, told the Austria
Press Agency on Saturday that the group will launch unannounced
blockades of the highway if measures are not taken to protect the
delicate Alpine environment.
</P>
<P>
   Before Austria joined the EU in 1994, a transit agreement was
signed limiting the number of heavy trucks that could cross the
republic's Alpine highways. But the EU has long ignored the limits
and traffic along the highway has nearly doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring Switzerland has solved its Alpine pollution problem
by building up its rail system to carry trucks over the mountains.
Because the trains run on electricity, they generate considerably
less pollution than the fuel-burning vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   In Switzerland, trains carry three times as much freight over
the Alps as trucks do -- practically the reverse of the situation in
Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Vienna has talked about forcing more trucks off the roads and on
to the rails, but EU regulations prevent them from doing so. The
Austrians have tried to raise tolls on the roads to discourage
truck traffic, but this has also sparked protest from the EU.
</P>
<P>
   The current transit agreement between Austria and the EU runs
out in 2003. Alpine dwellers and environmentalists are hoping to
see improvements in the next version.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not accept that as of 2003 truckers will be allowed
free access to Alpine highways,'' Transitforum leader Fritz
Gurgiser said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 1636 </TRAILER>
