<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Bush Tie In Newsweek Poll  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrat Al Gore and Republican George Bush
each had 45 percent support in a Newsweek presidential poll
released Saturday, with 10 percent of registered voters undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also asked about the candidates' ideas for changes in
the Social Security system to keep it viable in coming decades.
While most surveyed did not know which candidate had proposed what
plan, the vice president's was approved by 67 percent of the
respondents, while the Texas governor's drew 51 percent support.
</P>
<P>
   Only 18 percent knew Gore wants to create a supplemental savings
program, with workers allowed to put up to $2,000 a year in
tax-deductible savings with matching government contributions based
on income. Just 34 percent knew Bush would allow workers to invest
some of their Social Security payroll taxes in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The random telephone survey by Princeton Survey Research
Associates of 750 adults was conducted on June 22-23. The margin of
error was plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The results were consistent with the most recent Newsweek poll,
taken June 1-2. It showed a statistical dead heat, 44 percent for
Bush and 43 percent for Gore, with 13 percent undecided.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
