<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five plead guilty in racially motivated attack  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CENTRAL ISLIP, N.Y. (AP) - Three men and two women have pleaded
guilty to attacking a black man from New Jersey outside a Long
Island bar solely because of his race.
</P>
<P>
   While being questioned by authorities Friday, all five admitted
they hurled racial slurs at Gregory Jean-Pierre at the Road House
Pub in Centereach last Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Manganello, 21, Nicholas Leocata, 23, and his brother,
Joseph Leocata, 27, of Centereach, N.Y., all pleaded guilty to
second-degree attempted assault and aggravated harassment. Raechal
Dunham, 22, and Bobbie-Jo White, 27, also of Centereach, pleaded
guilty to aggravated harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Pierre, 24, of Plainfield, N.J., and two white friends were
taunted by a large group when they entered the bar. The bar's owner
threw everyone out, and the assault began in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Pierre and his friends tried to escape, but members of the
crowd, wielding beer bottles, set upon him and one of his friends,
Brian Moran, 27, of Coram, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The Leocata brothers and Manganello admitted punching and
kicking Moran. The three escaped into a store where one of the men
worked, but the attackers broke down the door and continued the
assault, police said. The third man was not injured.
</P>
<P>
   In return for their pleas, the Leocatas are to serve 90 days in
jail, 700 hours of community service and three years' probation.
They also must attend a racial-sensitivity course at the Suffolk
Probation Department.
</P>
<P>
   Manganello got the same sentence, but he is to serve only 30
days in jail. Dunham and White are to be sentenced to three years'
probation and 280 hours of community service and must attend the
racial-sensitivity course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
