<HEADLINE> New Haven man cleared in Central Park attacks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - A New Haven man who surrendered to New
York police in connection with the Central Park attacks following
the National Puerto Rican Day Parade has been cleared of criminal
charges, the New York County District Attorney's office said.
</P>
<P>
   Aerial Boxill, 28, was released but remains under investigation
by the district attorney's office, said spokeswoman Barbara
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have evaluated the case and we have decided not to
prosecute ... now,'' Thompson told the New Haven Register. ''We're
still investigating this defendant's participation ... and if
additional evidence surfaces, we will evaluate and consider
charging the defendant at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxill surrendered to detectives Thursday, while two New York
men were apprehended by police. All three were charged with one
count of sexual abuse and one count of riot. Two others were
arrested and charged with sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Police are still seeking 17 suspects in the June 11 attacks.
</P>
<P>
   A grand jury also indicted a ninth man on Thursday in connection
with the assaults on 57 women, who have told police they were
doused with water, chased, stripped, molested or assaulted. Several
others have reported being victims of robberies or attempted
robberies.
</P>
</TEXT>
