<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Europe Seeks Cooperation  </HEADLINE>
By MISHA SAVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   SZEGED, Hungary (AP) -- A decade after abandoning communism, most
central European countries are still struggling to catch up
economically with the continent's more affluent Western states, 16
foreign ministers said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from countries of the Central European
Initiative were meeting in southern Hungary to discuss regional
issues and how to become more competitive with their Western
European neighbors, especially the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no vacuum in economic life, but there is very fierce
competition,'' said Janos Martonyi, foreign minister of Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   Only two states at the convention, Italy and Austria, were EU
members. The others -- Albania, Belarus, Bosnia, Bulgaria, Czech
Republic, Hungary, Macedonia, Moldova, Poland, Romania, Slovakia,
Slovenia and Ukraine -- spoke of an urgent need for globalization
and integration of the European community.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 countries have a combined population of 230 million and a
total gross product of $2 trillion. But these factors alone are not
enough, delegates said.
</P>
<P>
   The less fortunate countries, particularly those affected by
recent wars in the Balkans, ''need to show they can help
themselves,'' said Stefano Pontecorvo, a representative of a U.S.
initiative called Stability Pact to develop the region.
</P>
<P>
   The pact has earmarked $1.1 billion for the region's
infrastructure, and almost as much is envisaged for developing the
private sector, education, media, environmental protection, refugee
return and other needs.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia's foreign minister, Tonino Picula, said his nation was
anxious to see specific benefits from the pact's 200 or so planned
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia was absent from the meeting, due to the international
isolation of its hard-line President Slobodan Milosevic. But the
country's problems were not ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Belgrade regime moves Serbia (the main Yugoslav republic)
farther away from the international community,'' Martonyi said.
''We cannot sit back with our arms crossed and do nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   A final document adopted at the meeting suggested support for
Serbia's democratic forces, but gave no fresh ideas on what to do
with the rogue leader and his regime, which has been outlawed by
the West. The other Yugoslav republic, Montenegro, was praised for
breaking with Milosevic's central government.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to show to the Serbian people that the international
community ... is not against them,'' said Romania's foreign
minister, Petre Roman, referring to last year's NATO bombing
launched to end Milosevic's crackdown on ethnic Albanian
separatists in Serbia's Kosovo province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
