<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, June 24, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Rebels Release Four Hostages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- A Red Cross official confirmed today that the gunmen
holding Fiji's deposed government hostage in parliament released their four
remaining female captives, including a minister in the ousted Cabinet. The four
women were among 31 hostages being held at the parliamentary complex in the
capital, Suva. ''They were taken out under heavy police escort and delivered to
their homes if they live in Suva, or to hotels,'' said John Scott, head of
Fiji's Red Cross.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Six Dead in More Indonesian Clashes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Fierce fighting between Muslims and Christians
flared for a fourth day in the capital of the Maluku Islands on Saturday,
leaving at least six people dead, officials said. Five Muslims and at least one
Christian soldier were killed when gangs of each faith exchanged gunfire and
fought with swords and spears early in the day in Ambon. The street battle took
place not far from a police complex that was set on fire when fighting erupted
Wednesday. Saturday's deaths brought to at least 41 the number of people killed
in four days, including four soldiers and two policemen.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Accepts Court's Elian Decision
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ABOARD AIR FORCE TWO (AP) -- Al Gore accepts a federal court decision that
moves Elian Gonzalez closer to returning to Cuba, an aide to the vice
president's campaign said today. ''We're going to respect the decision of the
court,'' spokesman Chris Lehane said aboard Air Force Two as Gore flew from San
Francisco to Miami. ''At this point, we'll wish what's best for the boy,''
Lehane said. Many political observers feel Gore's standing with Cuban American
voters, particularly in South Florida, has been hurt by the Clinton
administration's efforts to return Elian to Cuba.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Navy Ready To Resume Vieques Bombing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- The U.S. Navy said today it is ready to resume
bombing on Vieques island in the biggest training since a fatal accident last
year prompted a yearlong occupation of the target range. Protesters vowed to
block the exercises, and a general assembly of citizens was convened outside the
gates to the range's Camp Garcia to discuss strategy. Protesters will be chosen
to trespass on to the range, but only after bombing has begun, said activist
Hector Pesquera, who added organizers don't want a spontaneous rush of
demonstrators that could put lives in jeopardy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Seeks More For Drug Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- President Clinton wants to use $58 billion from the
growing budget surplus to help senior citizens pay for prescription drugs in
2002, revising an earlier proposal and offering more generous Medicare benefits
than current Republican plans. ''We have the money to do this now and do it
right,'' Clinton said today in his weekly radio address. Clinton outlined the
package he intends to send to Congress this week: a drug subsidy in 2002, a year
earlier than House Republicans are offering, and a $4,000 cap on an individual's
annual out-of-pocket medicine costs, compared with $6,000 under the GOP plan.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Arafat in Cairo To Discuss Mideast
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat flew to Egypt on
Saturday from Tunisia, where he had blamed Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak for
a lack of progress in the peace negotiations. Arafat was in Egypt for
discussions Sunday with President Hosni Mubarak. The essential problem, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency quoted Arafat as saying before leaving Tunisia, ''is
Barak's insistence not to delegate to the Israeli negotiators the necessary
mandate during the talks with the Palestinian side.'' He also cited ''Israel's
procrastination in implementing the signed agreement,'' for a lack of results,
MENA reported.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Announces New Web Site
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The government is consolidating its 20,000 Web sites into
a single Internet location offering information from grants and contracts to an
individual's benefits, President Clinton said today. ''Whether you want crucial
information in starting a small business, or you want to track your Social
Security benefits, you can do it all in one place, 24 hours a day, seven days a
week,'' he said in his first exclusively World Wide Web address to announce the
project. The site, http://www.firstgov.gov, should be operating within 90 days.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fusaichi Bidding War Heats Up
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Fusaichi Pegasus, the Kentucky Derby winner and
Preakness runner-up, might be retired soon and the bidding war for his stud
career is heating up, the Lexington Herald-Leader reported. In Saturday's
editions, the newspaper said that horse farms in the Bluegrass and overseas
already were in the bidding for Fusaichi Pegasus' potentially lucrative stud
career, with talk he might race only once more, in the Breeders' Cup Classic at
Churchill Downs in November. ''I've heard as high as $60 million,'' said Rich
Decker, president of WinStar Farm in Versailles.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
