<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NJ Airport Man Dies of Meningitis  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Some passengers who landed on a flight from
Israel were notified Saturday that they might have been exposed to
meningococcal meningitis by a fellow passenger who died after
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials identified 13 people on El Al flight 17 from
Tel Aviv who were sitting in close proximity to the stricken
passenger, Joseph Ferraro, 20, of Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   All but one of the 13 had been notified by Saturday afternoon
that they should see a doctor as a precaution and consider
preventive antibiotic therapy.
</P>
<P>
   It was not known how Ferraro had contracted meningitis, but
health officials said there was no reason to believe there were any
further cases.
</P>
<P>
   Meningococcal meningitis is a bacterial infection of the
membranes around the brain and spinal cord. The symptoms include
fever, neck stiffness and headache. It is transmitted only through
close contact, such as transmission of saliva through kissing or
sharing utensils.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro died at 7:07 p.m. Friday, about two hours after he
arrived at Newark International Airport. Police were notified
Ferraro needed help and took him to a hospital, where he died.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro had been visiting Israel on a group bus tour sponsored
by a Jewish youth group. The Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention identified 89 people who were on the tour with him and
were notifying them of the possible risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 1711 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000624.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Meatpacker Recalls Ground Beef  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Canadian packing plant of IBP Inc.
voluntarily recalled 46,000 pounds of ground beef products Saturday
because of possible contamination with E. coli 0157:H7, the second
recall in two days for the United States' largest beef processor.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department's Food Safety and Inspection Service
said IBP-Lakeside Packers in Brooks, Alberta, produced the products
May 31 and shipped them to Kansas, Kentucky and Tennessee, as well
as to locations in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   All products sold in the United States were packed in 10-pound
vacuum-packed tubes, with eight tubes per case. Shipping cases were
marked L0231BH, L0311BH, L0791BH. Tubes under recall are marked
003800152A (or B), with one of the following codes: 81 GRD BEEF; 86
GRD BEEF; 73 GRD BEEF.
</P>
<P>
   The inspection service said the possible contamination was
discovered in laboratory tests by a customer in Canada and reported
to Canadian authorities, who relayed the warning to the USDA.
</P>
<P>
   No ailments have been reported from any of the recalled meat.
</P>
<P>
   In a release, the Lakeside plant said most of the beef was to
have been processed by grocers or restaurants before being sold to
consumers, which means no brand names or product codes are
available for home checks.
</P>
<P>
   IBP acquired the Lakeside Farm Industries in 1994, IBP's first
wholly owned subsidiary outside the United States. IBP is based in
Dakota Dunes, S.D.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, IBP recalled 266,000 pounds of ground meat produced
May 13 at a plant in Geneseo, Ill., also for possible E. coli
0157:H7 contamination.
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria can cause bloody diarrhea and dehydration.
Children, the elderly and people with suppressed immune systems are
the most susceptible.
</P>
<P>
   The government recommends cooking all ground beef to at least
160 degrees to destroy bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.fsis.usda.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
