<DOCNO> APW20000624.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Canadian Party Chooses Leader  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY (AP) -- Members of the Canadian Alliance voted Saturday
to chose a leader for the new political party they hope will unify
conservatives and topple the governing Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
   The result of the vote, expected late Saturday night, should
indicate whether the Alliance and its core support from the former
Reform Party has been able to poach disgruntled Conservative Party
members.
</P>
<P>
   Before launching the Alliance three months ago, the Reform Party
had grown to become the official opposition in Parliament. Alliance
leaders say the new movement offers Canadians a change after seven
years of Liberal Party rule under Prime Minister Jean Chretien.
</P>
<P>
   Saying it stands for true representative democracy -- illustrated
by its one-member, one-vote system to choose a leader instead of a
convention of delegates -- the Alliance stands for the fundamental
conservative principles of decentralized federal power, low taxes
and reduced debt.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty over how the new party would deal with volatile
social issues, such as abortion, has illustrated the divisiveness
within Canada's political right, similar to the ideological rifts
among U.S. conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Four major candidates were vying for the leadership post
Saturday, with the winner to become the opposition leader in
Parliament and a major challenger for prime minister in
parliamentary elections next year. If none of the candidates gets
50 percent of Saturday's vote, a runoff between the top two will be
held July 8.
</P>
<P>
   Glitches and irregularities marred early voting, which began
Wednesday by telephone from remote areas and Quebec province. Some
members complained they never received security information needed
to cast a telephone vote, while others in eastern Quebec's Gaspe
region said they had received membership cards though they never
joined the Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   One candidate, Tom Long, apologized for what he called
overzealous party workers who purchased hundreds of the $6.50
memberships for people without telling them.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance's chances for defeating the Liberals depend on its
ability to grow in Ontario, the most populous province, as well as
in Quebec and other eastern regions.
</P>
<P>
   When it formed in March, almost all of its 70,000 members were
from the Reform Party, which in its 13 years has never won a
Parliament seat west of Manitoba. The Alliance says it now has
200,000 members, making it Canada's largest party. But this week's
irregularities cast doubt on that figure.
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party founder and leader Preston Manning engineered the
Alliance's creation as a way to forge a nationwide conservative
movement by attracting disillusioned supporters of the Conservative
Party, which last governed under Brian Mulroney in the 1980s and
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Manning and Long, an Ontario political strategist, both ran in
Saturday's leadership contest, along with former Alberta Treasurer
Stockwell Day and British Columbia politician Dr. Keith Martin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 1809 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000624.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dallas' JFK Memorial Rededicated  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- The John F. Kennedy Memorial was rededicated
Saturday in a ceremony that paid homage to the assassinated
president.
</P>
<P>
   Since the memorial's dedication in 1970, its concrete walls had
become stained and chipped. The monument was further tarnished by a
recent graffiti attack.
</P>
<P>
   The three-month restoration attempted to bring the monument
closer to its original state and included the installation of
interpretive panels to help answer questions posed by visitors over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   The panels detail the concept behind the memorial's boxlike
structure -- an ''open tomb'' tribute to someone whose remains lie
elsewhere. Kennedy is buried in Arlington National Cemetery near
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The monument, which consists of four 30-foot-high concrete
walls, is located two blocks east of where the president was killed
by a sniper's bullet on Nov. 22, 1963. Inside, an 8-by-8-foot slab
of gray granite is inscribed with JFK's name.
</P>
<P>
   Services and materials for the $80,000 restoration were donated
by 10 construction-related companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 1810 </TRAILER>
