<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man gets 10 years in robbery of nun  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PATERSON, N.J. (AP) - A Passaic man was sentenced to 10 years in
prison for his role in the beating and robbery of a nun who was
attacked during her early morning walk.
</P>
<P>
   Giovany Rubio, 24, had been acquitted of robbery and assault in
May, but convicted of conspiracy to commit robbery in the Dec. 14,
1997, assault on Sister Maria De Lillo.
</P>
<P>
   De Lillo, a 59-year-old teacher with the Blessed Sacrament Roman
Catholic Church, was taking an early morning walk when she was
attacked. Her assailant beat her, stole a gold ring from her finger
bearing the mark of a crucifix and three chains from around her
neck, leaving her on the sidewalk with a broken nose, bleeding on
the brain and bruising. She was hospitalized in critical condition
following the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ''What was taken from her were the only material objects that
meant anything to her,'' Robert Pringle, the county senior
assistant prosecutor, said at the Friday sentencing. ''Most
important was her crucifix ring that she wore as a symbol to her
devotion to God - the same way I wear my wedding ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubio's attorney argued that Rubio's co-defendant, Juan
Giraldez, was solely responsible for the attack. Giraldez pleaded
guilty and was sentenced to seven years in exchange for his
testimony against Rubio.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors presented eyewitnesses who named Rubio and said
specks of the nun's blood were found on his coat.
</P>
<P>
   State Superior Court Judge Joseph J. Riva said Rubio was at risk
to commit another crime, and said that the jury's decision to
convict him on the conspiracy charge indicated members did not
believe Rubio's claim that he was asleep in bed at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ''This defendant could not see fit to express to Sister Maria
how sorry he is for what occurred,'' Riva said. ''That tells me
that he lacks remorse and compassion even today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-24-00 1835 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000624.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Niagara Falls tower to be refurbished, not demolished  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) - A recommendation to renovate the
Prospect Point observation tower next to the American Falls is due
within a month, parks officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The state has pulled back on a $20 million plan to demolish the
tower, called ''hideous,'' ''a monstrosity,'' and ''a bridge to
nowhere,'' by Gov. George E. Pataki in 1998 when he first announced
plans to tear it down.
</P>
<P>
   The demolition plan included high-speed elevators to take
tourists to the Maid of the Mist boats but State Parks Commissioner
Bernadette Castro told The Buffalo News the project would be too
costly and dangerous to carry out.
</P>
<P>
   Castro said a ''panel of experts is still studying every
alternative'' to the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The state is considering installing faster elevators and
shortening the tower. The elevators currently take visitors to the
top of the 280-foot tower for views of the American and Canadian
falls and to the bottom of the gorge and to the Maid of the Mist
sightseeing boats.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the new elevators was to cut down on
lines for the Maid of the Mist tour boats. The proposed elevators
would have carried 2,500 people to the gorge every hour compared
with about 800 people an hour in the peak summer season, said
Jonathan M. Schultz, Maid of the Mist Corp.'s vice president of
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The waiting time to get aboard the boats from the U.S. side can
be as long as two hours in the summer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Maid of the Mist Corp. two years ago said it would
contribute $5 million toward the cost of the project, since the
tower is the only access on the U.S. side to the boats. Now, the
company is waiting to see what the state decision will be, said
Maid of the Mist president James V. Glynn.
</P>
<P>
   Once heralded as an engineering marvel, the observation tower at
Prospect Point between the Rainbow Bridge and the American Falls
has been a sore point for years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
