the official opposition in Parliament.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Navy Ready To Resume Vieques Bombing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- The U.S. Navy said today it is ready to resume
bombing on Vieques island in the biggest training since a fatal accident last
year prompted a yearlong occupation of the target range. Protesters vowed to
block the exercises, and a general assembly of citizens was convened outside the
gates to the range's Camp Garcia to discuss strategy. Protesters will be chosen
to trespass on to the range, but only after bombing has begun, said activist
Hector Pesquera, who added organizers don't want a spontaneous rush of
demonstrators that could put lives in jeopardy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore, Bush Tie In Newsweek Poll
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrat Al Gore and Republican George Bush each had 45
percent support in a Newsweek presidential poll released today, with 10 percent
of registered voters undecided. The poll also asked about the candidates' ideas
for changes in the Social Security system to keep it viable in coming decades.
While most surveyed did not know which candidate had proposed what plan, the
vice president's was approved by 67 percent of the respondents, while the Texas
governor's drew 51 percent support.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Rebels Release Four Hostages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- A Red Cross official confirmed today that the gunmen
holding Fiji's deposed government hostage in parliament released their four
remaining female captives, including a minister in the ousted Cabinet. The four
women were among 31 hostages being held at the parliamentary complex in the
capital, Suva. ''They were taken out under heavy police escort and delivered to
their homes if they live in Suva, or to hotels,'' said John Scott, head of
Fiji's Red Cross.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
El Al Passenger Dies of Meningitis
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Some passengers who landed on a flight from Israel were
notified today that they might have been exposed to meningococcal meningitis by
a fellow passenger who died after arrival. Health officials identified 13 people
on El Al flight 17 from Tel Aviv who were sitting in close proximity to the
stricken passenger, Joseph Ferraro, 20. All but one of the 13 had been notified
that they should see a doctor as a precaution.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tyson Defeats Savarese in 38 Seconds
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GLASGOW, Scotland (AP) -- Mike Tyson knocked down Lou Savarese with a left
hook about 12 seconds into their fight Saturday night at Hampden Park, then
stopped him several seconds later. After Savarese got up at the count of 5,
Tyson landed several more punches. Referee John Coyle stepped between the
fighters to halt the action. Tyson went around the referee and hit Savarese with
two more punches. When the crowd realized the fight had been stopped, the boos
showered down on the ring on this cold, rainy night. The official time was 38
seconds.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
