<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Green Party Adopts Platform  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN K. PAULSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- The Green Party adopted a platform Saturday
focusing on political reform, human rights, the environment and
corporate responsibility as members prepared to nominate consumer
advocate Ralph Nader for president.
</P>
<P>
   While delegates to the national convention of the Association of
State Green Parties debated their platform, Nader said his 50-state
tour had given him ''the distinct feeling that America wants a
change, a change from the dominance of the two major political
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader said the major parties offer little more than
''Band-Aids'' for health, child poverty, job security and other
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party is focusing on people who feel left out of the
democratic process because ''money counts more than citizen
participation at the grass roots,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nader said that four years ago, when he sat out most of the
campaign as the Green Party candidate while the party tried to get
organized, fewer than 50 percent of the eligible voters cast
ballots. He said the Green Party is counting on some of those
nonvoters this year to pull support from the two major political
parties and force them to face the issues.
</P>
<P>
   Nader also criticized Republicans and Democrats for refusing to
include him in debates.
</P>
<P>
   ''Neither George W. Bush nor Albert Gore want to face new ideas.
They want to keep the presidential election an insider game,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two others, Jello Biafra and Stephen Gaskin, also are seeking
the Green Party nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The platform, which passed by more than a two-thirds majority,
included a major change over term limits. Platform chairman Steve
Schmidt said the party abandoned term limits this year and came out
in favor of proportional representation, which he said gives
independent voters more power.
</P>
<P>
   The 317 delegates from 39 states also rejected an attempt to
delete support for the Brady gun-registration bill from the
platform. Nevada delegate Sandi Rizzo told conventioneers it would
be ''political suicide'' for a Green Party candidate in her state
to support gun control, but delegates refused to debate the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said the party also supported the right to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   The platform also endorsed gay and lesbian rights in housing,
jobs, civil marriage, benefits and child custody and the right to
openly embrace sexual orientation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 1926 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000624.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Undecided May Control Japan Vote  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH COLEMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Only one hurdle stands between Japan's ruling
coalition and victory in Sunday's lower house elections: a legion
of undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori's Liberal Democrats are in a
position of strength ahead of the vote. Polls show them with firm
chances of holding onto power, and the opposition has failed to
present a credible challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The only question mark left as polls opened Sunday morning was a
large chunk of voters who have not yet decided whom to cast ballots
for -- a volatile bunch that could conceivably tip the scales
against the government. In a recent survey in Asahi newspaper, 52
percent of respondents said they supported no party, and 70 percent
of those said they were still undecided whom to vote for.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days ago, Mori -- in the type of verbal gaffe that has
typified his short term in office -- said he hoped the undecided
would stay in bed on election day.
</P>
<P>
   At his final campaign stops Saturday, Mori pushed hard on his
top election theme: that the Liberal Democratic Party and its two
coalition partners are the only ones who can provide the stability
needed to see Japan through its economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to make sure that the economy is in recovery and to
push economic reforms,'' he told a crowd outside a train station in
a residential Tokyo neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Barring an unexpected exodus of undecided voters to the
opposition, however, the ruling party should not face much trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the premier's unpopularity and the still-weak state of
the economy, the conservative LDP on its own is expected to win at
least 241 seats, a simple majority of the 480-seat chamber. Polls
show that majority could reach as high as 263 seats.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the 12-day campaign has been the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Japan logged a year of economic growth -- a slight 0.5 percent --
in the fiscal year that ended March 31 after two years of
shrinkage, part of a series of signs showing the economy may be
coming to life after a decade-long slump.
</P>
<P>
   But troubles remain. The unemployment rate is still at 4.8
percent, near a record high, and bankruptcies are rising. Corporate
restructuring and other social problems are believed to be behind
the country's rising suicide and crime rates.
</P>
<P>
   The LDP and its coalition partners have vowed to continue a
massive, two-year fiscal spending program aimed at propelling the
economy into recovery. Mori has already ordered work on another
supplemental budget.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, meanwhile, has focused on the hefty price-tag
for that policy: a public debt that totals more than 130 percent of
Japan's gross domestic product. The Democrats, the largest
opposition party, are pushing for a tax increase to shore up
government finances.
</P>
<P>
   ''Japan is teetering on the edge of a cliff, and only the
Democratic Party can show the people how to turn the situation
around,'' party leader Yukio Hatoyama said to a crowd gathered in
the rain outside a Tokyo train station Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the opposition has struggled to put together a credible
alternative to LDP rule. Hatoyama has been coy about who his
coalition partners would be, and it is difficult under any
circumstances to win votes by promising a tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that interest is high in the election, which
follows a tumultuous couple of months in Japanese politics.
</P>
<P>
   Mori took over on April 5, days after then-Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi suffered a stroke and fell into a coma, provoking a
succession crisis. The government delayed telling the nation of
Obuchi's illness for a full day, and accusations of a cover-up
dogged the first month of Mori's rule.
</P>
<P>
   Mori's selection as prime minister also quickly came under fire.
The premier had never held the posts of foreign or finance
minister, two jobs considered stepping stones to the prime
ministership, and he was widely criticized as a policy lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   He also has had a hard time avoiding controversial statements.
He told a religious group that Japan was a ''divine nation'' and
was so severely attacked for conjuring up memories of Japan's
wartime emperor-worship that he called a special news conference to
explain himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
