<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Royals 8, Athletics 3  </HEADLINE>
By ROB GLOSTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- The Oakland Athletics built a nine-game
winning streak on home runs and big comebacks. When their offense
fizzled Saturday against a pitcher making his first start of the
season and three relievers, the streak ended.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Quinn hit a three-run homer and Luis Ordaz added three RBIs
with a two-run single and a sacrifice fly in the Kansas City
Royals' 8-3 win over the A's.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland, which hit .368 during the winning streak and averaged
more than 10 runs a game, was held to two extra-base hits -- a
first-inning double by Jason Giambi and a double by Randy Velarde
in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Reichert, making his first start of the year after 26 relief
appearances, allowed one run in four innings.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Bottalico (7-1) pitched the final 2 2-3 innings for the
win, surviving a bases-loaded jam in the seventh when first baseman
Mike Sweeney made a leaping grab of Eric Chavez's liner to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn's eighth homer of the season knocked Heredia out in the
sixth. Ordaz had his two-run single in the fifth, when the Royals --
who broke a three-game losing streak -- also got an RBI single by
Jeff Reboulet.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Heredia (9-5) allowed six runs and eight hits in 5 1-3
innings. He's 2-4 at home this season, 7-1 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Giambi, Miguel Tejada and Velarde had RBI singles for the A's.
</P>
<P>
   Giambi, who went 3-for-4 with a walk, has reached base safely in
nine consecutive plate appearances before striking out in the
ninth. He went 3-for-3 with two walks in the A's 10-6 win over the
Royals on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Giambi, who had a homer and two doubles on Friday night, is
hitting .500 (19-for-38) against the Royals this season.
</P>
<P>
Notes: A's pitching coach Rick Peterson was ejected in the sixth
by plate umpire Gerry Davis, the first ejection for Oakland this
season. ... The nine-game winning streak matched the fourth longest
in Oakland history and was the longest in the AL this season. ...
Quinn's homer was just the eighth allowed by Heredia in 94 innings
this season. ... Oakland's Terrence Long extended his hitting
streak to 13 games with a pair of singles. ... Bottalico, who began
the season as the Royals' closer but lost the job in May, leads
Kansas City in wins and his five saves leave him just one behind
Jerry Spradlin for the team lead. ... Giambi, who came in second in
the AL with 72 RBIs, has 21 RBIs in his last 15 games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
