<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, June 24, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Veterans Mark 'Forgotten War'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) -- Fifty years after North Korea attacked the South as
Koreans slept, Korean War veterans from the United States and elsewhere gathered
at former battlegrounds this week to remember. The war lasted three years, cost
millions of lives and left a small peninsula nation divided. One American
veteran brought the South Korean flag he saved from his days as a U.S. marine in
the early 1950s; another returned to the port city of Inchon where his flotilla
launched the daring landing that would change the course of the 1950-53 war.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Rebels Release Four Hostages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Gunmen holding Fiji's deposed government hostage released
their four remaining female captives Sunday, including three ministers in the
ousted Cabinet, a Red Cross official said. The four women were among 31 hostages
being held at the parliamentary complex in the capital, Suva. John Scott, head
of the Red Cross in Fiji, said they were freed around 2:30 a.m. Sunday. ''They
were taken out under heavy police escort and delivered to their homes if they
live in Suva, or to hotels,'' Scott said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Albright Hopes Limited on Mideast
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- When Secretary of State Madeleine Albright makes her
third trip in a month to the Middle East this week, she would like to invite
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to a
summit with President Clinton. But Albright does not think either the Israeli or
Palestinian leader is ready to go to the summit with a reasonable expectation
that an agreement could be hammered out with Clinton's hands-on intervention, a
senior U.S. official familiar with her thinking said Saturday. She also realizes
that a summit cannot be delayed until the two leaders are nearly in accord, said
the official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Seeks More Money For Drug Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- President Clinton wants to use $58 billion from the
growing budget surplus to help senior citizens pay for prescription drugs in
2002, revising an earlier proposal and offering more generous Medicare benefits
than current Republican plans. Clinton outlined the package he intends to send
to Congress this week in his weekly radio address today: a drug subsidy in 2002,
a year earlier than House Republicans are offering, and a $4,000 cap on an
individual's annual out-of-pocket medicine costs, compared with $6,000 under the
GOP plan.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mexican Candidate's Rally Starts
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Battling last-minute charges of illegal foreign
financing, Mexico's top opposition candidate for president closed his campaign
in the capital Saturday with a mass rally in the country's central plaza.
Chanting ''Fox! Fox! Fox!,'' crowds poured through the narrow streets of the
city center and nearly filled the massive Zocalo plaza for Vicente Fox of the
conservative National Action Party. In the final weekend of campaigning before
the July 2 election, Fox was in a statistical dead heat in the polls with
Francisco Labastida of the Institutional Revolutionary Party.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Navy Ready To Resume Vieques Bombing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- The U.S. Navy said today it is ready to resume
bombing on Vieques island in the biggest training since a fatal accident last
year prompted a yearlong occupation of the target range. Protesters vowed to
block the exercises, and a general assembly of citizens was convened outside the
gates to the range's Camp Garcia to discuss strategy. Protesters will be chosen
to trespass on to the range, but only after bombing has begun, said activist
Hector Pesquera, who added organizers don't want a spontaneous rush of
demonstrators that could put lives in jeopardy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore, Bush Even In Newsweek Poll
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrat Al Gore and Republican George Bush each had 45
percent support in a Newsweek presidential poll released today, with 10 percent
of registered voters undecided. The poll also asked about the candidates' ideas
for changes in the Social Security system to keep it viable in coming decades.
While most surveyed did not know which candidate had proposed what plan, the
vice president's was approved by 67 percent of the respondents, while the Texas
governor's drew 51 percent support.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tyson Defeats Savarese in 38 Seconds
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GLASGOW, Scotland (AP) -- Mike Tyson knocked down Lou Savarese with a left
hook about 12 seconds into their fight Saturday night at Hampden Park, then
stopped him several seconds later. After Savarese got up at the count of 5,
Tyson landed several more punches. Referee John Coyle stepped between the
fighters to halt the action. Tyson went around the referee and hit Savarese with
two more punches. When the crowd realized the fight had been stopped, the boos
showered down on the ring on this cold, rainy night. The official time was 38
seconds.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
