<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cayuga tribe enters casino sweepstakes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - A casino operator is hedging its bets in
its drive to build a gaming center in New York, contacting a third
Indian tribe as it searches for a partner.
</P>
<P>
   The Cayugas are the latest tribe in the state to be approached
by Catskill Development LLC about operating a casino and the
harness-race track at the Monticello Raceway in Sullivan County.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Halftown of Erie County, spokesman for the Cayuga Nation,
said the tribe is reviewing a proposal for it to operate a casino,
the Syracuse Newspapers reported in Saturday's edition.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd A. Kaplan, a spokesman for Catskill Development LLC,
declined comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Halftown said the Cayugas' governing body has not seen details
of the proposal or made a decision on whether to consider the
casino idea.
</P>
<P>
   The Sullivan County casino would be about 90 miles northwest of
New York City on Route 17, closer to the city than casinos in
Atlantic City, N.J. and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ''It almost looks like the developers down there are going down
the list of the Six Nations tribes. We must be next in line after
the Oneidas and Mohawks,'' Halftown told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Rex Hackler, spokesman for the federal Bureau of Indian Affairs,
said his office has not seen anything on a Cayuga-Catskill
Development partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Seneca-Cayuga Tribe of Oklahoma, said it was
interested in a Catskill casino, chief Jerry Dilliner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Oneida Nation was the first tribe approached in 1995 but a
disagreement over profit sharing led that tribe to strike out on
its own and open Turning Stone Casino Resort on reservation land in
Verona, Oneida County.
</P>
<P>
   Around September 1995, the developers turned to the St. Regis
Mohawks of Northern New York. But the Mohawks, who opened a casino
of their own on their St. Regis reservation on the U.S.-Canadian
border in March 1999, hooked up with Park Place Entertainment, one
of the world's largest gambling companies.
</P>
<P>
   The state Assembly Friday delayed action on a measure requiring
legislative and local authorization before Indian tribes can open
gambling casinos on non-tribal lands. Currently, only the
governor's approval is required. The state Senate passed the bill
last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-24-00 2000 </TRAILER>
