<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Avs Trade Ozolinsh to Carolina  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MOSSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Faced with difficult negotiations in trying to
re-sign All-Star defenseman Sandis Ozolinsh, the Colorado Avalanche
traded him to the Carolina Hurricanes on Saturday in a deal also
involving defenseman Nolan Pratt and four draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   Ozolinsh, a restricted free agent who made $4 million last
season but who slumped in the latter stages of the playoffs, became
expendable after the Avalanche signed veteran defenseman Ray
Bourque to a one-year, $5.5 million contract on June 14.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's sad to see him go because he is a quality player,''
general manager Pierre Lacroix said. ''There was a lot of interest.
''The last five years, it has been pretty clear that we are
building for the future while winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven other key Avalanche players are due new contracts for next
season, putting a burden on Colorado's already hefty payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the NHL entry draft on Saturday, the Avalanche dealt
Ozolinsh and a second-round pick (No. 32) to Carolina for Pratt and
the Hurricanes' first three picks (Nos. 14, 47 and 63).
</P>
<P>
   With the 14th choice, Colorado selected center Vaclav Nedorost
of the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Ozolinsh, 27, is one of the better offensive-minded defensemen
in the NHL. The Latvian had 52 points including 16 goals last
season, his eighth in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Lacroix insisted that potentially difficult talks with Ozolinsh
had ''nothing to do with'' the trade, and said the organization,
even with new ownership, has no intention of cutting costs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We felt that the timing was there to make that kind of
decision,'' he said. ''I called Sandis before we announced it. It
was not a fun call to make. It's the nature of the business, and we
have to live with it. I'm sure he understands.''
</P>
<P>
   By dealing Ozolinsh and moving up in the draft, Lacroix was able
to obtain a player he coveted. Because Boston took Colorado's
first-round choice at No. 27 in the Bourque deal, the Avalanche
would have been without a first-rounder.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, 24, was Hartford's fourth choice in the 1993 draft. In 64
games last season, the 6-foot-2, 195-pounder had three goals, one
assist and 90 penalty minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pratt will add a physical presence to our defensive corps,''
Lacroix said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 2001 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
