<HEADLINE> Fatal crash cancels air show F-14 demonstration  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - The U.S. Navy has canceled a demonstration
of the F-14 Tomcat because the team that was to fly the fighter jet
was killed Sunday in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The Tomcats were to be part of the Syracuse International Air
Show on July 8 and 9. On Sunday, though, pilot Lt. William Joseph
Dey and radar intercept officer Lt. David Erick Bergstom died when
the F-14 plunged into woods near the airport in Willow Grove, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The men flew from the Fighter Squadron 101 stationed at Oceana
Naval Air Station in Oceana, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was told that was our pilot,'' Syracuse Aviation
Commissioner Charles Everett said Friday. ''They have several
teams, and that was the one that crashed.''
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's crash, the Navy said it had no plans to ground
its F-14s or to cancel participation in air shows. The cause of
Sunday's crash is under investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
