<HEADLINE> Gentry Wins Women's Trap Title  </HEADLINE>
By KEITH PARSONS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Cindy Gentry is going to her second straight
Olympics. This time, she gets to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Gentry, of Stone Mountain, worked as an official in the shooting
events in the 1996 Atlanta Games. On Saturday, she won the women's
trap title -- and lone spot on the U.S. Olympic team -- at the USA
Shooting National Championships and Final Olympic Team Selection
Match at Wolf Creek Trap and Skeet Range.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was really something to come back four years and later
and make the Olympic team,'' Gentry said.
</P>
<P>
   Scores from a spring trial at Fort Benning were added to totals
from this event.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Bade and Josh Lakatos qualified for the two men's trap
spots on the U.S. team, repeating what turned out to be their
medal-winning appearances from 1996. Lakatos won the silver and
Bade the bronze in those Games.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say it was harder to make the team this time,'' said
Bade, who won the men's trap national title. ''There was more
pressure this time, so I think Josh and I both earned our spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Bade handled the pressure well, missing just two targets in his
final 100 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ''I started kind of slow, but there at the end, I just got in a
rhythm,'' said Bade, who trains at the U.S. Olympic Center in
Colorado Springs, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Gentry entered this competition 12 points behind leader Joetta
Dement but steadily made up ground each day.
</P>
<P>
   In the final round Saturday, Gentry's score of 92 was three
points better than the next highest, and 13 more than Dement.
Theresa DeWitt finished second overall, eight points behind Gentry.
</P>
<P>
   Dement had back-to-back 79s on the final two days and dropped to
third. She and DeWitt are both members of the U.S. Army
Marksmanship Unit at Fort Benning.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Herman finished third in men's trap, five back of
Lakatos.
</P>
<P>
   Lakatos said he was lucky to finish the competition after he
suffered back spasms Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I couldn't even walk, much less shoot,'' said Lakotos, who
lives in Pasadena, Calif. ''For some reason, we had a late time
Friday, so I got some treatment and was able to go. I couldn't bend
my knees or bend over, I just had to stand straight up and try not
to move.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm surprised I was even shooting. So to make the team, that
is really a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   In other events Saturday, Colombian Andres Torres took a
six-point advantage in men's running target, and Terry Anderson of
Dallas holds a one-point lead on John Bickar of Colorado Springs in
rapid fire pistol.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 2026 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
