<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, June 24, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Navy Hasn't Resumed Vieques Bombing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- The U.S. Navy by this evening had not carried
out plans to conduct a military exercise on Vieques island, as up to 200
protesters threatened to invade the range if bombing started. According to plans
the Navy filed with the Puerto Rican government, five warships plan to fire up
to 600 shells at the range and aircraft would drop between 550 and 830 dummy
bombs -- including 500-pound and 1,000-pound bombs -- during two to five days of
exercises to start ''approximately'' today. The exercise would be the largest
since a fatal accident last year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Announces New Web Site
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The government is consolidating its 20,000 Web sites into
a single Internet location offering information from grants and contracts to an
individual's benefits, President Clinton said today. ''Whether you want crucial
information in starting a small business, or you want to track your Social
Security benefits, you can do it all in one place, 24 hours a day, seven days a
week,'' he said. The site, http://www.firstgov.gov, should be operating within
90 days.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Envoy Seeks Israeli Withdrawal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- U.S. envoy Dennis Ross met Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators Saturday to try to reach agreement on Israeli troop withdrawals and
other issues, American and Palestinian officials said. Ross met at an
undisclosed location Saturday night with Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat and
his Israeli counterpart Oded Eran, an American official said on condition of
anonymity. The outstanding problems include release of Palestinian prisoners
from Israeli jails, opening of a second ''safe passage'' for Palestinians across
Israeli territory, the Palestinian demand for control of an airfield near
Jerusalem and the third Israeli troop withdrawal in the West Bank.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Undecided May Control Japan Vote
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Only one hurdle stands between Japan's ruling coalition and
victory in Sunday's lower house elections: a legion of undecided voters. Prime
Minister Yoshiro Mori's Liberal Democrats are in a position of strength ahead of
the vote. Polls show them with firm chances of holding onto power, and the
opposition has failed to present a credible challenge. The only question mark
left as polls opened Sunday morning was a large chunk of voters who have not yet
decided whom to cast ballots for.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Rebels Release Four Hostages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Gunmen holding Fiji's deposed government hostage released
their four remaining female captives Sunday, including three ministers in the
ousted Cabinet, a Red Cross official said. The four women were among 31 hostages
being held at the parliamentary complex in the capital, Suva. John Scott, head
of the Red Cross in Fiji, said they were freed around 2:30 a.m. Sunday. ''They
were taken out under heavy police escort and delivered to their homes if they
live in Suva, or to hotels,'' Scott said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Veterans Mark 'Forgotten War'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) -- Fifty years after North Korea attacked the South as
Koreans slept, Korean War veterans from the United States and elsewhere gathered
at former battlegrounds this week to remember. The war lasted three years, cost
millions of lives and left a small peninsula nation divided. One American
veteran returned to the port city of Inchon where his flotilla launched the
daring landing that would change the course of the 1950-53 war.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mexican Candidate's Rally Starts
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Battling last-minute charges of illegal foreign
financing, Mexico's top opposition candidate for president closed his campaign
in the capital Saturday with a mass rally in the country's central plaza.
Chanting ''Fox! Fox! Fox!,'' crowds poured through the narrow streets of the
city center and nearly filled the massive Zocalo plaza for Vicente Fox of the
conservative National Action Party. In the final weekend of campaigning before
the July 2 election, Fox was in a dead heat in the polls with Francisco
Labastida of the Institutional Revolutionary Party.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tyson Defeats Savarese in 38 Seconds
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GLASGOW, Scotland (AP) -- Mike Tyson knocked down Lou Savarese with a left
hook about 12 seconds into their fight Saturday night at Hampden Park, then
stopped him several seconds later. After Savarese got up at the count of 5,
Tyson landed several more punches. Referee John Coyle stepped between the
fighters to halt the action. Tyson went around the referee and hit Savarese with
two more punches. When the crowd realized the fight had been stopped, the boos
showered down on the ring. The official time was 38 seconds.
</P>
