<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Hopes Limited on Mideast  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- When Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
makes her third trip in a month to the Middle East this week, she
would like to invite Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to a summit with President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright does not think either the Israeli or Palestinian
leader has a reasonable expectation that an agreement could be
hammered out with Clinton's hands-on intervention at a summit, a
senior U.S. official familiar with her thinking said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   She also realizes that a summit cannot be delayed until the two
leaders are nearly in accord, said the official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Israeli-Egyptian summit President Carter held in 1978
at Camp David, Md., Clinton in any case would have a lot of work to
do to get Barak and Arafat together on a settlement that deals with
the future of Jerusalem and Palestinian aspirations for a state.
</P>
<P>
   Albright believes Clinton, like Carter, should be prepared to
take a risk on a summit that could blow up, the official said. But
the late Egyptian President Anwar Sadat and the late Israeli Prime
Minister Menachem Begin were a lot closer when former Secretary of
State Cyrus R. Vance invited them to the summit 22 years ago and
they accepted.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Palestinian-Israeli dispute is a lot more
complicated than the one then between Israel and Egypt. And even
Carter had to do some serious mediating and then make a trip to the
Middle East before the 1979 peace treaty was signed.
</P>
<P>
   Sadat could insist on recovering all the land Egypt had lost in
the 1967 Six-Day war with Israel and get every bit of it for a
peace treaty. Arafat may have to settle for less.
</P>
<P>
   So, Albright's trip, which begins Tuesday evening in Jerusalem,
is a negotiating mission, not simply one of issuing invitations to
be hosted by Clinton after the July 4th holiday.
</P>
<P>
   And, the senior U.S. official said, there may not be enough of a
basis for an agreement between them at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Albright needs word from both Barak and Arafat that they are
ready to make the ''hard decisions'' that are necessary for a
compromise accord, the official said. And Arafat, particularly, has
not yet accepted the notion that neither side can get 100 percent
of what it wants.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, now in control of about 40 percent of the West Bank and
Gaza, is demanding virtually all of the territory as well as East
Jerusalem, where he would set up his capital. Barak has signaled he
is prepared to yield more of the West Bank and some suburbs of
Jerusalem, and accept a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   But the gap between them remains wide. Also, the issue of
Palestinian refugees demanding at least compensation on the grounds
they were uprooted by the establishment of a Jewish state in 1948
remains unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has been telling Arafat that with
U.S. help he has a chance to reach some of his goals, although he
is holding out for realization of all of his dreams, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's Mideast specialist, Dennis B. Ross, has preceded her
to the region for talks with the two sides. They have agreed on
Sept. 13 as a deadline for an agreement, and Clinton has made peace
in the Middle East his No. 1 foreign policy priority.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, meeting with U.S. Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo on
Friday, said more Palestinian flexibility would achieve an
agreement ''that would serve the interests of both sides,''
although ''neither side would achieve its dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright flew to Poland on Saturday from South Korea for a
100-nation conference on democracy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 2122 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000624.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Awards Honor Indian Film Stars  </HEADLINE>
By ERICA MICHELSTEIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- There was no shortage of glitz and glamour
Saturday as Bombay's biggest films stars were honored at the
International India Film Awards, their cinematic equivalent of the
Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   The love story ''Hum Dil De Chuke Sanam'' picked up three top
prizes including the award for best picture. The film's leading
lady, Aishwarya Rai, a former Miss World, won the best actress
award while Sanjay Leela Bansai won for best director.
</P>
<P>
   Sanjay Dutt was named best actor for his role as a vendor in the
murder tale ''Vaastav.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Miss Universe Sushmita Sen took home the best supporting
actress for her role in ''Biwi No. 1'' and Anil Kapoor won best
supporting actor for the film ''Taal.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 Indian movie stars were among 3,000 guests
attending the ceremony at London's Millennium Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said they hoped to gain international recognition for
Bollywood, the nickname given to Bombay, which boasts the world's
second largest film industry after Hollywood. The awards show was
to be broadcast to 122 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights was the presentation of a lifetime
achievement award to martial arts legend Jackie Chan.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is so exciting to be here,'' said Chan. ''I'm good at
action but not so good at speeches. I don't only do action and
comedy you know. I'm a good singer and I'm not too expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Actor Sunil Dutt and musician Lata Mangeshkar received standing
ovations when they received honors for invaluable contributions to
India's cinema.
</P>
<P>
   ''I owe this to the people of my country who give great love to
me,'' Dutt said, accepting his award.
</P>
<P>
   The film ''East is East'' also won an award for outstanding
achievement in international cinema. India produces between 600 and
800 films every year.
</P>
</TEXT>
