<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Break Blockade in Colombia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Riot police on Saturday broke up a road
blockade by Colombian Indians protesting oil exploration by a U.S.
company.
</P>
<P>
   A representative of the U'wa Indian tribe claims two of the
protesters were shot by police. Their wounds were not
life-threatening, Yurisa Tegria told The Associated Press by
telephone from Cubara, a town near the Venezuelan border where the
incident occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Police denied that account, saying an officer fired one warning
shot in the air when a protesters went for his gun. National police
operations director Gen. Alfonso Arellano said nobody was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians were trying to prevent trucks from reaching the
construction site where U.S.-based Occidental Petroleum Corp. is
preparing to drill over a field thought to hold huge crude
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The 8,000-member U'wa nation has been fighting for more than
five years to halt the company's plans, at one point threatening
mass suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The U'wa say drilling violates the sanctity of the earth, and
will bring guerrilla violence to their homeland. The government
says the group is being intransigent, and argues a major new oil
find would benefit most Colombians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-24-00 2143 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000624.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mutiny 4, Fusion 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Mamadou Diallo scored two goals and
Carlos Valderrama had three assists to lead the Tampa Bay Mutiny
past the Miami Fusion 3-2 Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The victory avenged the Mutiny's 4-1 loss to the Fusion on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo's second goal and 15th of the season gave Tampa Bay a 2-0
lead at the 48th minute. Valderrama broke through the Miami defense
and sent a pass to Eric Quill on the left wing, where Quill
centered a pass to Diallo, who headed it in a shot from the 6-yard
box.
</P>
<P>
   Miami cut the deficit to 2-1 in the 68th minute when Jay Heaps
kicked in a shot inside the 6-yard box off a corner kick from
Martin Machon.
</P>
<P>
   But Tampa Bay struck back at the 76th minute on Kevin Anderson's
goal. Anderson received a pass from Valderrama and unleashed a
25-yard shot into the upper left-hand corner of the Fusion goal.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Williams scored Miami's second goal at the 90th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay remains in second place in the Central Division with a
9-8 record and 27 points. Miami is third in the Eastern Division at
6-8-4 and 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Mutiny took a quick lead when Diallo scored at the eighth
minute of the match. Mutiny midfielder Steve Ralston centered a
pass to Diallo, who headed in a 10-yard shot past Fusion goalkeeper
Nick Rimando.
</P>
<P>
   Miami had its best first-half scoring opportunities in the final
minutes as Henry Gutierrez and Welton took open shots that were
stopped by Tampa Bay goalkeeper Scott Garlick.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had players ejected in the first half and were forced
to play 10 a side.
</P>
<P>
   Miami defender Tyrone Marshall was red-carded at the 31st minute
for fouling Diallo from behind. Tampa Bay's Chad McCarty was sent
off nine minutes later after fouling Welton from behind.
</P>
</TEXT>
