<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, June 24, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Rebels Release Four Hostages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Gunmen holding Fiji's deposed government hostage released
their four remaining female captives Sunday, including three ministers in the
ousted Cabinet. The four women were among 31 hostages being held at the
parliamentary complex in the capital, Suva. They were freed around 2:30 a.m.
Sunday. Under heavy police escort, they were taken first to see family members,
then to see a team of trauma specialists who gave them medical checkups and
counseling, officials said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Vieques Protesters Claim Victory
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Protesters claimed victory today after the U.S.
Navy did not begin a planned bombing exercise on Vieques island -- the largest
since a fatal accident prompted a yearlong occupation of the target range.
''This is one more triumph in the fight against the Navy,'' activist Hector
Pesquera said at a meeting of protesters today near the Navy facility, Camp
Garcia. About 200 protesters had said they would invade the range if bombing
began. But by this evening, the exercise, which the Navy had earlier said would
begin ''approximately Saturday'' had failed to materialize.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Green Party Adopts Platform
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- The Green Party adopted a platform today focusing on political
reform, human rights, the environment and corporate responsibility as members
prepared to nominate consumer advocate Ralph Nader for president. While
delegates to the national convention of the Association of State Green Parties
debated their platform, Nader said his 50-state tour had given him ''the
distinct feeling that America wants a change, a change from the dominance of the
two major political parties.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Announces New Web Site
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The government is consolidating its 20,000 Web sites into
a single Internet location offering information from grants and contracts to an
individual's benefits, President Clinton said today. ''Whether you want crucial
information in starting a small business, or you want to track your Social
Security benefits, you can do it all in one place, 24 hours a day, seven days a
week,'' he said. The site, http://www.firstgov.gov, should be operating within
90 days.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Envoy Seeks Israeli Withdrawal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- U.S. envoy Dennis Ross met Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators Saturday to try to reach agreement on Israeli troop withdrawals and
other issues, American and Palestinian officials said. Ross met at an
undisclosed location Saturday night with Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat and
his Israeli counterpart Oded Eran. The outstanding problems include release of
Palestinian prisoners from Israeli jails, opening of a second ''safe passage''
for Palestinians across Israeli territory, the Palestinian demand for control of
an airfield near Jerusalem and the third Israeli troop withdrawal in the West
Bank.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Undecided May Control Japan Vote
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Only one hurdle stands between Japan's ruling coalition and
victory in Sunday's lower house elections: a legion of undecided voters. Prime
Minister Yoshiro Mori's Liberal Democrats are in a position of strength ahead of
the vote. Polls show them with firm chances of holding onto power, and the
opposition has failed to present a credible challenge. The only question mark
left as polls opened Sunday morning was a large chunk of voters who have not yet
decided whom to cast ballots for.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Catholics Pack Chicago Stadium
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Soldier Field was transformed into a house of worship for
about 30,000 Roman Catholics who gathered Saturday to renew their commitment to
Christianity. The ''Field of Faith'' was a Eucharist held as part of the Jubilee
Year 2000 celebration for the Archdiocese of Chicago. Heavy rainstorms kept
attendance lower than expected for the open-air event. The event brought
together the largest assembly of Catholics in Chicago since Pope John Paul II
celebrated Mass here in 1979.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tyson Defeats Savarese in 38 Seconds
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GLASGOW, Scotland (AP) -- Mike Tyson knocked down Lou Savarese with a left
hook about 12 seconds into their fight Saturday night at Hampden Park, then
stopped him several seconds later. After Savarese got up at the count of 5,
Tyson landed several more punches. Referee John Coyle stepped between the
fighters to halt the action. Tyson went around the referee and hit Savarese with
two more punches. When the crowd realized the fight had been stopped, the boos
showered down on the ring. The official time was 38 seconds.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cardinals Defeat Dodgers 6-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Mark McGwire homered for the sixth time in seven games, the
550th of his career and his major league-leading 28th of the season, helping the
St. Louis Cardinals beat the Los Angeles Dodgers 6-1 tonight. Alan Benes won his
first game in 2&AMP;frac12; years, pitching on a day filled with 5 hours, 55 minutes
of rain delays.
</P>
